<FILEID>AP-NR-04-29-89 0146EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-BRF--CarWashTrap     04-29 0176</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Car Wash Trap,0181</SECOND>
<HEAD>Woman Who Was Stuck In Car Wash Hospitalized</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who stopped for a late-night car
wash got trapped in the building overnight and suffered carbon
monoxide poisoning because the engine was running the whole time.
   Jamie Denise Stewart, 23, was unconscious when an attendant
opened the car wash at a gas station Friday, police said. She
apparently had tried to ram the door with her automobile, they said.
   Ms. Stewart was in guarded condition Friday night at Vanderbilt
University Medical Center, hospital officials said.
   Tests found Ms. Stewart had drugs and alcohol in her system,
police said.
   ``At some point she may have become unconscious before the doors
closed,'' Lt. Tommy Jacobs said.
   Ms. Stewart went to the station for cigarettes and a car wash
between 2 a.m. and 3 a.m. Friday, police said.
   An attendant later closed the automatic car wash doors by remote
control, believing the woman had already left.
   Police said Ms. Stewart was trapped in the building for three to
four hours.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890429-0010 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-29-89 0146EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     04-29 0292</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0301</SECOND>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PEORIA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It isn't playing well with city leaders, but
a student who can smell a winner has come up with a scent that
could have all America turning its nose up at Peoria.
   ``Essence of Peoria'' is being promoted as the Midwest's
``finest industrial fragrance,'' a potion that reeks of the ethanol
plants that permeate this city.
   ``It's the smell of very old beer _ kind of an egg sulfur smell.
When the wind is just right, it's the smell you get all over
Peoria,'' said David Cook, the Bradley University student who
developed the formula with the help of chemists.
   Cook packaged 1,000 bottles of his fragrance and got several
area hotels and novelty stores to sell it as a gag, but the
response has been far from comical.
   ``It's a gag that's going crazy,'' Cook said. ``I've already
sold out half my stock, about 300 bottles, in just one week on the
market. ... I broke even on my investment three days ago. I'll
definitely be producing more.''
   ``I don't know if people in Peoria will buy it because all they
have to do is open their windows. But it's going to do real well
with visitors,'' said D.J. Shadid, owner of gift shops in three
hotels.
   But city officials who hired a public relations firm in 1987 to
polish the city's image would like to get rid of the stink over
``Essence.''
   ``I admit it's a clever idea but it disappoints me because I
don't want to see someone making fun of our city,'' Mayor Jim
Maloof said. ``We've tried so hard the last few years to change our
image. Hopefully this product, and the smell, will fade away.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
