<FILEID>AP-NR-04-29-89 0146EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-TritiumSupply Bjt   04-29 0620</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tritium Supply, Bjt,610</SECOND>
<HEAD>Critics Say Government Cried Wolf on Nuclear Material Shortage</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The decision by Energy Secretary James D.
Watkins to wait until 1990 to resume production of a gas needed for
nuclear warheads shows clearly that supplies of the gas are not as
tight as the government once claimed, critics say.
   The Pentagon asserted last fall that unless production resumed
by this summer the nuclear weapons factories would face a shortage
of tritium, a scarce, highly radioactive gas used to boost the
explosive power of nuclear warheads.
   But critics have said they believe the earlier warnings about a
tritium crisis were aimed at galvanizing congressional support for
the Energy Department's proposal to spend $6.8 billion to build two
new tritium-producing reactors.
   ``That whole scenario was orchestrated for political purposes by
certain people in the Pentagon,'' Chris Paine, an aide to Sen.
Edward Kennedy on nuclear defense issues, said in an interview
Friday. ``It's not as serious as they suggested.''
   Watkins told Congress and the Pentagon this week that he had
decided the department's tritium-producing reactors in South
Carolina would not be restarted until early next year, at the
earliest.
   Watkins said he wanted more time to assess safety conditions at
the Savannah River Site, where the three reactors have been sitting
idle since last spring. They were shut down for mechanical repairs
and to address safety problems.
   The reactors are the nation's only source of tritium, which
decays relatively quickly, so replacement supplies are needed to
maintain the nuclear arsenal. One hundred grams of tritium becomes
50 grams after 12 years _ a far faster rate of decay than
plutonium, another vital material used to make nuclear weapons.
   The tritium hiatus has had no immediate affect on weapons
production, since the arms factories can dip into a tritium
reserve. The size of that reserve is classified, and the government
has not said exactly how long the surplus will last.
   Several times earlier this year, the Energy Department's chief
of defense programs, Troy Wade, testified at congressional hearings
that the problem had become ``critical.''
   ``If a reactor is not restarted this year, then the supply of
tritium could be reduced to such an extent that the nuclear
stockpile may be affected,'' Wade told a Senate Armed Services
subcommittee in early February.
   Private analysts who monitor the government's weapons program
have been saying for months that the Energy Department and the
Pentagon have overstated the supply problem.
   Dan Reicher, an attorney for Natural Resources Defense Council,
an environmental group that has sued the Energy Department to block
restart of the Savannah River reactors, said Friday that Watkins'
decision undercuts the idea of a looming crisis.
   ``The longer we go without production the more we see there is
no tritium crisis,'' he said in an interview. ``Again the Pentagon
and DOE have cried wolf.''
   Last week, 11 prominent U.S. scientists issued a joint statement
urging the Energy Department to hold off on restart of the Savannah
River reactors until the Soviet Union has been sounded about
possible negotiated cuts in nuclear materials.
   ``It is our considered view that there is no critical shortage
of tritium today and that claims of an imminent `crisis' distort
the true situation,'' the scientists said.
   They said enough tritium exists today to sustain a fully
adequate weapons stockpile for at least five years without new
production if better management techniques were used. Among these
would be the use of tritium from weapons scheduled for retirement
or held in storage.
   Watkins said in a letter to congressional committees last week
that he had ordered changes in the department's management of
tritium inventories, but he gave no details.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
