<FIRST>r i PM-MissUniverse     04-29 0172</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Miss Universe,0177</SECOND>
<HEAD>Miss France Disqualified From Miss Universe Contest Because of Age</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CANCUN, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Miss France has been disqualified from
participating in next month's Miss Universe contest because she is
too young, the Excelsior news service reported.
   Excelsior quoted Martin Kip, vice-president of the U.S.-based
organization Miss Universe Inc., as saying Peggy Zlotkowski would
have had to have been 17 years old in February to participate in
the contest.
   She turned 17 on March 30, the news service said late Friday.
   Excelsior said Ms. Zlotkowski was ``humiliated'' by the ruling
that she was too young to participate in the contest, which will be
aired by CBS-TV to an estimated 900 million viewers on May 23.
   She reportedly said she had not been informed of the age
requirement and didn't learn of her disqualification until after
she traveled from Paris to this Caribbean resort in southeastern
Mexico.
   Excelsior said another woman would be named to represent France.
   Seventy-seven women from around the world are to participate in
the contest.
