<FIRST>u i PM-Germany-Missiles Bjt   04-29 0549</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Germany-Missiles, Bjt,0568</SECOND>
<HEAD>West Germans Say Momentum Growing Against U.S. Stand On Missiles</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRENCE PETTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West German officials say NATO nations
are starting to line up against the U.S. and British views in a
major disarmament dispute within the Western alliance.
   Chancellor Helmut Kohl's call for superpower negotiations on
short-range nuclear weapons has placed him in a battle of wills
against both President Bush and British Prime Minister Margaret
Thatcher.
   Mrs. Thatcher and Kohl are scheduled to meet Sunday in West
Germany to discuss the issue.
   Foreign Minister Hans-Dietrich Genscher spent part of Friday
talking about the dispute, one of the most divisive in recent years
in the North Atlantic Treaty Organization, with U.S. Ambassador
Vernon A. Walters.
   A Foreign Ministry statement said ``both sides expressed their
belief that the alliance will jointly resolve the still-open
question of a formulation of a comprehensive (disarmament)
concept.''
   But there were no indications that would happen soon.
   Genscher's spokesman said seven of the 16 NATO members,
including West Germany, support Kohl.
   West Germany wants the United States to agree to talks with the
Soviet Union on the short-range weapons and notes that NATO decided
in favor of such negotiations in 1987.
   Most of NATO's short-range nuclear weapons are based in West
Germany and would be used exclusively on German soil in the event
of war.
   Washington rejects the West German insistence on negotiations,
saying talks on tactical nuclear arsenals should not begin as long
as the Warsaw Pact alliance has a superiority in conventional
forces.
   West German polls show that the electorate favors such talks.
The military reductions announced by Mikhail S. Gorbachev has made
the Soviet leader a popular figure in Western Europe.
   The dispute has led to lobbying efforts by both sides among the
NATO members.
   Genscher told Parliament on Friday, ``We can see that we are
finding more and more understanding for this position (for
negotiations) within the whole alliance.''
   Juergen Chrobog, Genscher's chief spokesman, told reporters six
other NATO countries are backing West Germany.
   Denmark, Belgium, Norway and Italy have announced their support
of Kohl and Chrobog said Greece and Spain also back him.
   France has not given a clear signal where it stands, but French
President Francois Mitterrand said last week: ``Nothing should be
done that will compromise the movement toward disarmament.''
   The Netherlands has offered to mediate between the feuding NATO
members, and Dutch Premier Ruud Lubbers plans to travel to Bonn on
Wednesday.
   Kohl is slated to travel to Rome on Tuesday for discussions with
Italy's leaders on the dispute, and Genscher will have talks in
Paris the same day with French Foreign Minister Roland Dumas.
   One West German official, speaking with the condition he not be
identified, said the government would stand firm.
   ``In past years the German point of view wasn't always put that
strongly in alliance matters, but right now German interests are at
stake,'' he said.
   With a growing mood for increased demilitarization, NATO is
hoping to present a showing of solidarity at its Brussels summit on
May 29-30.
   West Germany's pressure for negotiations on short-range nuclear
weapons comes as Kohl tries to improve his image. There have been
predictions he could lose next year's elections to the left-leaning
Social Democrats.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
