<FIRST>r w PM-US-Panama     04-29 0423</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Panama,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Panama Invites Carter, Ford to Panama to Monitor Elections</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Presidents Jimmy Carter and Gerald R.
Ford have been invited by authorities in Panama to monitor upcoming
national elections in that country, a Panamanian official said.
   Panamanian Foreign Minister Jorge Ritter said at a news
conference Friday evening that he informed a Carter emissary on
Wednesday the two former presidents would be welcome for the May 7
balloting.
   Ritter said Carter is held in high esteem by Panamanians because
of his role in negotiating the canal treaties that will revert the
waterway to Panamanian control at the end of the century.
   ``We are prepared to give him the warmest welcome,'' Ritter said.
   Spokesmen for Carter and Ford were unavailable for comment
Friday night.
   Ritter said Panamanian authorities are not eager to have foreign
observers in ``overwhelming numbers.'' He said the reason is that
the country lacks facilities to accommodate them and their presence
could impair the electoral process.
   The Bush administration has said that the Panamanian government,
led by the Defense Forces commander Manuel Antonio Noriega, is
preparing fraud on a massive scale to ensure victory in the
elections.
   The principal contest in the balloting matches the official
candidate, Carlos Duque, against Guillermo David Endara, who is
running on an anti-goverment coalition ticket.
   The election controversy was taken up Friday morning at a U.N.
Security Council session called at Panama's request.
   Ritter told the session the United States has supplied millions
of dollars to opposition candidates and has sent commandos, special
weapons and helicopters to Panama as well.
   He accused the United States of trying to subvert democratic
elections, set up a puppet, pro-Washington government and undermine
the canal treaties.
   ``U.S. plans of interfering in the Panamanian electoral process
have entered a phase of direct participation,'' Ritter told the
15-member council.
   ``The objective is undermining public order, causing chaos,
promoting widespread destabilization in the country around election
time and creating a pretext for military intervention in Panama.''
   In reply, U.S. Ambassador Thomas Pickering accused Panama's
government of blatantly interfering in the election process;
manipulating voters' lists; muzzling the opposition, press and TV;
and restricting access by impartial foreign monitors and
journalists.
   ``The moral bankruptcy of the regime of Gen. Manuel Noriega for
which Mr. Ritter speaks is well known,'' Pickering said.
   The United States does not recognize the Noriega-led government,
insisting that former President Eric Arturo Delvalle was ousted
illegally in February 1988 and continues to be the country's
legitimate authority.
</TEXT>
