<FILEID>AP-NR-04-29-89 0219EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-JapanFighter Bjt   04-29 0659</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan Fighter, Bjt,650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush, Critics Disagree on Jobs Impact of Deal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARTON REPPERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush says he wants to go ahead with
a controversial deal with Japan for joint development and
production of the new FSX jetfighter, despite congressional concern
over loss of American jobs and technology.
   Bush, announcing on Friday the agreement to make an advanced
version of the U.S. F-16 for deployment by Japan in the late 1990s,
declared that the deal was ``in the strategic and commercial
interests of the United States.''
   ``And we weighed this matter from the standpoint of trade, of
our industrial growth and technology transfer, as well as strategic
and foreign policy considerations,'' the president said.
   The announcement was made the same day the Office of Trade
Representative released a report listing Japan as one of the worst
users of trade barriers and, according to published reports,
recommended sanctions for refusing to open its markets to U.S.-made
cellular phones and mobile radios.
   Congressional critics were quick to respond to Bush's
announcement.
   ``President Bush claims that this giveaway will not cost the
American people a cent,'' said Rep. Richard A. Gephardt, D-Mo.,
chairman of the FSX Task Force and a House leader on trade issues.
``What's he going to tell the thousands of aerospace workers who
will lose their jobs as a result of this deal?''
   Gephardt's St. Louis district is the home of General Dynamics,
the American partner with Japan's Mitsubishi Heavy Industries in
developing the aircraft.
   Bush told reporters at the White House the United States ``will
have a 40 percent work share in the initial development stage of
this aircraft, and we will have a similar share when the aircraft
goes into production.''
   Development of the FSX is expected to cost about $1.2 billion,
while the production run is estimated to cost about $5 billion for
130 planes.
   ``There will be no cost to the American taxpayer and at the same
time the Japanese will improve their ability to carry their share
of the defense burden,'' Bush said.
   Addressing concerns over U.S. technology, Bush said: ``Sensitive
source codes for the aircraft's computer will be strictly
controlled. Access will be granted to only those codes that are
essential to complete the project.''
   Three administration officials who briefed reporters said that
for instance, the codes for the new F-16 digital flight control
computer, which just came out last year, will not be released to
the Japanese.
   Any new technology developed by the Japanese during the FSX
program will be available to U.S. firms, but Japan will be banned
from transferring to third countries or firms any technology
derived from the U.S.-built F-16 plane, the officials said.
   Congress has 30 days to review the agreement, signed Friday by
Secretary of State James A. Baker III and Japan's Ambassador Nobuo
Matsunaga.
   The House and Senate can reject it by a joint resolution of
disapproval. But if such a resolution is passed, a two-thirds
majority of both houses would be required to override a likely Bush
veto.
   Initial Capitol Hill reaction to the announcement was dominated
by critics of the FSX.
   Rep. Mel Levine, D-Calif., said he will mount a campaign to
scrap the plan because Japan could best help reduce the trade
deficit with the United States by purchasing U.S.-built F-16s ``off
the shelf.''
   Also speaking out against the decision was Rep. James J. Florio,
D-N.J., who said that ``we are giving our strongest competitor in
the world marketplace the expertise it lacks to directly challenge
America's leadership in international civil and military aircraft
sales.''
   Sen. Richard G. Lugar, R-Ind., a senior member of the Senate
Foreign Relations Committee, said he favors going ahead with the
deal.
   ``I'm encouraged by the agreement between the United States and
the Japanese, particularly on the work share, the (computer) source
codes and technology flowback,'' he said. ``And I hope that this
will ease congressional concerns about the FSX.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890429-0019 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-29-89 0223EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-ChickenInspections     04-29 0358</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Chicken Inspections,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>USDA Says Chicken Safe Despite Broken Glass</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Agriculture Department says it is
satisfied with a plan that let 6,500 chickens be sold one day after
a fluorescent light shattered into the vat where they were being
processed at a Georgia plant.
   ``We believe it was handled as it should have been,'' Karen
Stuck, chief of inspection at the department's Food Safety and
Inspection Service, said Friday. The skinned breast and drumstick
parts were shipped Wednesday from a ConAgra Inc. plant in
Gainesville, Ga., but company officials did not know their
destination.
   But a national union official insisted Friday on a recall.
``Once these small slivers of glass get in birds, there's no way to
tell it until you eat it or prick your finger with it,'' said
Delmer Jones, president of the National Council of Food Inspection
Locals of the American Federation of Government Employees.
   According to Ms. Stuck, a government inspector at the plant
originally had ordered the chickens in the vat condemned. The
company then appealed, proposing a salvage plan that was approved
by the same inspector and his two immediate supervisors, she said.
   Ms. Stuck said officials in Washington have reviewed all the
actions in the case and are satisfied with the approval of the
salvage plan, which involved skinning the chickens and discarding
the abdominal fats and back pieces.
   Walt Casey, a spokesman for ConAgra, said the company ``has a
very high comfort level that our product is safe.'' He accused
Jones of ``blowing smoke'' because of union problems with local
USDA officials.
   When the fluorescent light shattered into the vat, Casey said,
``We stopped the line and removed all the chickens that were
involved.
   ``We went through the skinning and deboning procedure, which is
not unusual in this type of circumstance, and we had the approval
and involvement of the USDA inspector there, and also approval from
his supervisor.''
   Casey said he did not know where the chicken parts involved in
the accident were shipped but added that he would not disclose the
destination if he did know.
   ``I'm not sure that's relevant,'' he said.
</TEXT>
