<FIRST>r a PM-BlackCadet     04-29 0343</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Black Cadet,0352</SECOND>
<HEAD>First Black Cadet To Graduate From West Point Finally Recognized</HEAD>
<DATELINE>THOMASVILLE, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first black to graduate from West
Point was honored by Georgia more than a century after his historic
achievement.
   A marker at the grave of Henry Flipper was unveiled Thursday by
Attorney General Michael Bowers, who called Flipper a hero and said
it was time ``we righted this great wrong.''
   For the descendants of Flipper, it wasn't the first time they
have waited for recognition.
   Flipper graduated from the academy 112 years ago. He was
court-martialed 108 years ago, but the Army overturned the
conviction 12 years ago and named part of the West Point library
after Flipper.
   Gwinnett County teacher Ray MacColl battled for 18 years to win
the recognition, and Flipper's niece, Irsle King of Valdosta, tried
to help her uncle gain a hearing during the last years of his life.
   Ms. King said she was pleased by the ceremony but wished the
honors had come while he was alive.
   Flipper was born into slavery in Thomasville. He moved with his
family and its owners to Atlanta, and after the Civil War attended
Atlanta University before winning nomination to West Point.
   Flipper was graduated from the academy in 1877, commanded an
all-black cavalry regiment in Oklahoma and then was put in charge
of the Fort Sill commissary. In 1881, he was charged with
embezzling $3,791 and with conduct unbecoming an officer.
   At a court-martial MacColl said was plagued with ``racism and
irregularities,'' Flipper was acquitted of theft but convicted of
unbecoming conduct.
   After Flipper was exonerated in 1977, West Point dedicated a
bust of him at the academy and named a portion of the library in
his honor. The academy also established an annual award in his name
for the cadet who has survived the greatest hardship.
   In 1978, Flipper's body was removed from an unmarked grave in
Atlanta, where he died in 1940 at the age of 84, and was reburied
near his parents' graves in Thomasville with full military honors.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
