<FIRST>r w PM-Jackson-Mayor     04-29 0554</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Jackson-Mayor,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jackson Says ``No'' to Reports He Wants Mayor's Job</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sources close to Jesse Jackson say he is
``strongly considering'' foregoing a third race for the presidency
in 1992 to run for mayor of the District of Columbia.
   A source, speaking on condition of anonymity, said Friday that
Jackson would consider the 1990 mayoral bid if embattled Mayor
Marion S. Barry Jr. decides against seeking a fourth term.
   Jackson denied Friday night that he is seeking to replace Barry,
a longtime ally, although he said in interviews published in two
newspapers today that has not ruled out running for the office if
Barry steps aside.
   ``I have not yet made a determination to run here,'' Jackson
told The Washington Post.
   Asked by a reporter at a hotel banquet here Friday night if he
was considering a race for mayor, Jackson said ``No.'' He also said
he has not talked to Barry about whether the mayor, who has been
dogged by reports about the city's skyrocketing murder rate and
friendship with a former city official convicted of cocaine
trafficking, will run.
   ``I've always supported the mayor,'' said Jackson, who last year
lost the Democratic presidential nomination to Massachusetts Gov.
Michael Dukakis.
   The two men, however, have talked about Jackson running for the
job if Barry does not seek a fourth four-year term, the source
close to Jackson, who spoke only on condition of anonymity, told
The Associated Press.
   The New York Times reported in today's editions that Jackson
said he would ``never run against Marion Barry.''
   But Jackson said, ``If he were not running, that's a different
story.''
   Jackson lives in Chicago, but The Washington Post report said is
speeding up plans to remodel a house he owns in Washington and
could move in by November. ``My family has not made that decision,
but we can't move before the house is finished,'' Jackson told the
Post.
   Jackson has repeatedly said that ``under no condition'' would he
run against Barry. The two men have been close friends and
political allies since their civil rights activities together in
the early 1960s.
   Barry, who has not said whether he will seek re-election, could
not be reached Friday night. The mayor's spokesman also was
unreachable.
   An effort to organize a mayoral campaign on behalf of Jackson
was launched two months ago by a member of the city school board
and a leader of the district's Statehood Party.
   Ann Lewis, a Democratic political strategist and an adviser to
Jackson in his presidential campaign, said Friday that comments
Jackson has made to political confidants indicate ``he does not
immediately reject'' running for mayor.
   ``I know he's been under a lot of pressure about this,'' Ms.
Lewis said. ``It's clear that they have reached him,'' she said,
referring to the draft-Jackson effort organized by school board
member R. Calvin Lockridge and Statehood Party leader Tom Chorlton.
   The two men had hoped to gather signatures from 100,000 of the
city's 300,000 registered voters on a petition supporting Jackson
for mayor, but Chorlton said the effort has been slowed by a lack
of volunteers.
   Jackson, who has never held elective office, could qualify for
the 1990 mayor's race by switching his voter registration from
Chicago to the district by November of this year.
</TEXT>
