<FIRST>u a AM-WomanAssaulted 1stLd-Writethru a0726 04-29 0555</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Woman Assaulted, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0726,0565</SECOND>
<HEAD>Security Tightened At Park; Four Suspects Denied Bail</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to CLARIFY that one of the suspects was
charged in a separate incident in the park; picks up 12th graf pvs, `Earlier,
Berkman...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY McSHANE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three suspects in the gang rape and beating of a
Central Park jogger were denied bail Friday during a raucous
hearing at which an angry judge almost ejected a defense lawyer for
a suspect in a related attack.
   A grand jury, meanwhile, indicted a sixth teen-ager in the
jogger's attack, and city officials announced a beefing up of
security in the area near the attack.
   ``This crime was an outrage which shocked every New Yorker,''
said Parks Commissioner Henry Stern at a Central Park news
conference.
   The new protection plan will include mounted police patrols,
increased police car surveillance and the use of police decoys,
officials said.
   ``Every once in a while something happens that is so shocking
and terrible that it brings about a tremendous counterattack,''
said Stern. ``I think that's what happened here.''
   On Friday afternoon, a grand jury indicted 14-year-old Kevin
Richardson, the only suspect who admitted raping the woman in his
statement to police. Six teen-agers are now charged as members of
the wolf pack who brutalized the woman during a night of
``wilding.''
   Richardson was charged with rape, attempted murder, assault,
sodomy, robbery and riot. He was held without bail pending a May 10
hearing.
   While Stern detailed the security changes, a confrontation
erupted at state Supreme Court between spectators and court
officers Friday morning when acting Justice Carol Berkman ordered
defense attorney Alton H. Maddox Jr. removed from court.
   Maddox had repeatedly refused to follow the judge's instructions
to sit down and remain silent during the hearing.
   As spectators stood and screamed at the officers to leave Maddox
alone, Berkman left the bench, and court officers entered the
courtroom with billy clubs and riot helmets. When the judge
returned five minutes later, Maddox and co-counsel Joseph Mack
turned and walked out.
   They returned 45 minutes later and the judge denied bail for
their client, 17-year-old Michael Briscoe, after an exchange with
Mack over his conduct. Briscoe is one of two teens being held for
an attack on a male jogger that same night.
   Earlier, Berkman refused to set bail immediately for three other
defendants _ Kharey Wise, 16; Antron McCray, 15; and Steve Lopez,
15 _ and told their attorneys to submit their bail applications in
writing.
   Assistant District Attorney Elizabeth Lederer, arguing against
bail, called the April 19 assault on the Wall Street investment
banker ``the most vicious and brutal crime in New York to date.''
   ``As a result of their rampage, a 28-year-old woman is lying
unconscious in Metropolitan Hospital,'' said Lederer. ``She was
raped, sodomized and brutally beaten, and then left bleeding for
hours in the thickest woods.''
   The victim, a native of suburban Pittsburgh, remained comatose
and on life-support systems Friday.
   In an effort to defuse any racial tensions caused by the attack,
Manhattan Borough President David Dinkins met Friday with about 60
community and religious leaders and said they would hold a
``massive assembly and march'' in the neighborhood where the rape
took place. It was tentatively set for May 7.
