<FIRST>r a PM-MiamiVice     04-29 0579</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Miami Vice,0595</SECOND>
<HEAD>Miami Vice Wraps Up; Debate Continues Over Effects On City</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILL LESTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Miami Vice,'' the fashion-conscious cop show that
once dominated television's Top 10, filmed its last episode this
week, and city leaders were unsure whether Vice has been a virtue.
   Most city officials would agree that the program brought a new
sense of excitement to Miami's tattered image, but some fear the
program's obsession with drug smugglers and violent crime may have
scared off tourists and outsiders.
   The final scenes were shot Thursday night at a luxurious house
in Miami Beach, and some of the cast and production crew held a
farewell party Friday night.
   The program is widely recognized for its influence on men's
fashion, television-filming techniques and rock-music scores for
television.
   As its popularity grew, life imitated art, and both Miami and
Miami Beach saw a boom in bright pastels and a glorification of art
deco.
   The producers of Miami Vice decided this season would be the
last season, saying the five-year show had run its course. Once one
of TV's most watched shows, A.C. Nielsen Co.'s end-of-the-year
ratings recently ranked the NBC show in 65th place.
   Television writer Anthony Yerkovich said in an interview that
his idea for the show came out of visits in the early 1980s, when
the area faced race riots, drug shootouts and waves of new
immigrants.
   ``It seemed to be a real border town, an American Casablanca _
with all the hopes and dreams that implies,'' Yerkovich said. ``The
city inspired the show in the sense that we had a vision of Miami
that wasn't connected to the reality of the town.''
   Sidney Levin, a founding member of the Beacon Council, which
promotes the city's business climate, said Friday that the
television show gave Miami ``the feeling of a new city, a city that
a lot of tourists had never seen.
   ``It made a fashion trend ... a Miami style. There hadn't been a
Miami style since the 1940s and '50s,'' Levin said.
   Some civic leaders said they winced when they heard the show's
title.
   ``Here came a show to be called `Miami Vice,' a shoot'em-up,''
Levin said. ``I think if you could have taken a vote that day, they
would have voted the show out of town.''
   He said many people who promote the city will be relieved to see
the show go because of its emphasis on violence and drugs.
   ``We were trying to combat an image problem,'' said former Dade
County manager Merrett Stierheim. ``We were always a target for
various publications that take a delight in beating on Miami.
   ``I want to say kind things,'' he said, ``but the jury is out as
to the total impact on Greater Miami.''
   The plot of the last show is strikingly similar to the first
one, aired Sept. 16, 1984. The main characters _ Sonny Crockett,
played by Don Johnson, and Rico Tubbs, played by Philip Michael
Thomas _ are sent to the fictional South American country of Costa
Morado to bring back a corrupt dictator to testify against
international drug traffickers. The ending is secret.
   The final show is scheduled to be shown May 21.
   Johnson and Thomas say they'll keep their ties to the community.
Johnson said he may open a restaurant and race powerboats, while
Thomas plans to open a theater for young actors.
   ``I'm not leaving Miami,'' Thomas said. ``This is home for me.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
