<FILEID>AP-NR-04-29-89 0515EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Japan-FSX     04-29 0290</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-FSX,0298</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japan Welcomes $7 Billion U.S.-Japan Agreement On FSX</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Japan Fighter, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S.-Japan agreement to jointly produce 130 new
FSX fighter jets for Japan will promote defense and technological
cooperation between the nations, officials said today.
   Defense Agency chief Kichiro Tazawa said in a statement that the
countries had reached a better understanding of each other through
their talks on the FSX craft, which is a new, more sophisticated
version of the American F-16 jet.
   President Bush announced in Washington Friday that the United
States will produce the FSX _ or fighter support experimental _
with Japan despite congressional concern over loss of U.S. jobs and
technology.
   ``The joint development of the aircraft will be extremely
important for defense cooperation between the United States and
Japan,'' Tazawa said in the statement.
   The Defense Agency late Friday decided to give the United States
a 40 percent share of the development and production of the jet.
   It also agreed to allow the United States to protect the
computer codes used to help fly and control the plane, which will
be a joint project of General Dynamics and Mitsubishi Heavy
Industries.
   Mitsubishi told Kyodo News Service it expects the project, to
begin at the end of June, to cost about $7.2 billion.
   An unidentified Japanese diplomat said Japan expects the
agreement to become a ``model of technology sharing'' between Tokyo
and Washington.
   Bush told reporters Friday that he had agreed to go ahead with
the project because he was convinced that ``co-development of this
aircraft is in the strategic and commercial interests of the United
States.''
   Congress has 30 days to review the agreement, and the House and
Senate can reject it with a joint resolution.
</TEXT>
