<FILEID>AP-NR-04-29-89 0525EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r p PM-TaxElection     04-29 0478</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tax Election,0494</SECOND>
<HEAD>Voters Judge Tax Revision Plan</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Polls open at 6 a.m. CDT; should stand.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN SAYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Buddy Roemer's tax revision plan,
heralded by proponents as a break with Louisiana's past and
condemned by opponents as a windfall for big business, fell into
the hands of the voters today.
   The controversial plan would overturn decades of populist
tradition by raising taxes and cutting the load on businesses.
   Roemer has pushed for a radical restructuring of the tax system,
saying it is vital in order to create jobs in the state with the
nation's highest unemployment rate, which is higher than 11 percent.
   ``Jobs now,'' the governor said of his plan.
   But opponents led by Rep. David Duke, the former Ku Klux Klan
leader who won a special election in February, criticized the plan
as harmful to individual taxpayers.
   The referendum is on a proposed constitutional amendment
authorizing the Legislature to make basic changes in the tax system.
   A new tax code approved by legislators during a special session
in late February and early March would take effect if the amendment
passes. Among other things, the new code would increase individual
income taxes and give businesses incentives to move into the state
and expand.
   The package also would raise the gasoline tax by 4 cents a
gallon to fund a $1.4 billion in improvements on highways, airports
and shipping ports.
   If the referendum is defeated, the Legislature would have to cut
more than $600 million from an already tight budget, which Roemer
has said is impossible.
   Oil companies have footed much of the state's bills for decades,
but the recession in the industry has cut tax revenues drastically
in recent years and cast the state into a series of budget crises.
   Through a blitz of radio and television spots financed by more
than $1.2 million from backers, Roemer has touted the plan as a way
of creating jobs and ending Louisiana's dependence on the petroleum
industry.
   But opponents say most of the tax breaks will be enjoyed by the
state's 1,000 largest corporations, many of which are not
labor-intensive, and that new jobs will not be created.
   ``It's bad for business, it's bad for the consumer,'' said Duke.
``You don't raise taxes in a recession.''
   Secretary of State Fox McKeithen said he expected more than 40
percent of the state's 2 million registered voters to cast ballots.
   The plan would cost an extra $126 million over the current tax
load. But opponents point out that as of July 1, the tax load
increase would be $526 million.
   Last summer, the Legislature approved a one-year sales tax
increase of $500 million to keep the government solvent. That
increase was scheduled to expire on July 1, but Roemer's package
would make about $400 million of that tax permanent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890429-0029 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-29-89 0528EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-WorkersMemorialRdp     04-29 0488</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Workers Memorial Rdp,0502</SECOND>
<HEAD>Labor Unions Honor Those Who Died On The Job</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICIA BIBBY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   On the first observance of Workers Memorial Day, the
government's record on worker safety was criticized, a bugler
played ``Taps,'' and roll calls were read of the hundreds of people
who died on the job in the United States last year.
   From northern Maine to southern California and Honolulu, workers
paused Friday to remember those killed in job-related accidents.
The events were organized by labor unions to highlight workplace
safety.
   The unions chose Friday because it is the 19th anniversary of
the founding of the Occupational Safety and Health Administration.
   An estimated 10,000 people are killed each year on the job. The
jobs that carry the highest risk of fatal injury, according to the
government, are in mining, transportation, construction and
agriculture.
   Many decried unsafe working conditions.
   ``Working men and women of America will not tolerate that type
of exploitation,'' AFL-CIO President Lane Kirkland said at a
gathering of 500 people in Kansas City, Mo. ``We will fight until
the day of the spilling of workers' blood in the workplace is but a
memory.''
   In Philadelphia, members of six unions gathered at noon to read
the names of the 252 workers killed in the state last year from
industrial accidents. As a bagpiper played ``Amazing Grace,'' 252
red carnations were dropped into the Delaware River.
   Elsewhere in Pennsylvania, union members, some wearing black
armbands, gathered at the Capitol in Harrisburg to mourn co-workers
who died on the job. In Pittsburgh, United Steelworkers officials
read the names of 23 other workers killed at work in the last two
years.
   ``The body count alone is a call to action,'' said Julius
Uehlein, president of the Pennsylvania AFL-CIO.
   In Texas, politicians and union officials condemned the state's
No. 1 rank in job-related deaths.
   U.S. Rep. John Bryant, D-Texas, said much of the ``annual
carnage'' in the workplace could be avoided and criticized the
Reagan administration for cutting the OSHA budget by 25 percent
since 1980.
   Bryant said President Bush seeks further cuts. Texas leads the
nation with an average of 781 deaths per year, said Joe Gunn,
secretary-treasurer of the Texas AFL-CIO.
   A moment of silence was called for in New Jersey to remember
those who died or were injured in job-related accidents.
   ``The purpose of this is to commemorate the lives of those
individuals and to support new efforts for new safety efforts on
the job,'' said Rick Engler, spokesman for the New Jersey
Industrial Union Council, AFL-CIO.
   In Utah, a bugler played ``Taps'' and the flag outside the Salt
Lake Union Labor Center was lowered to half-staff as about 50
people gathered for the memorial.
   And in Honolulu, a memorial service was held to honor flight
attendant Clarabelle ``C.B.'' Lansing, the only person to die when
the roof of Aloha Air Flight 243 ripped open exactly one year
earlier.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
