<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--LateMedal     04-29 0167</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Late Medal,0172</SECOND>
<HEAD>Retired Serviceman Receives Medal _ 45 Years Late</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GRAND RAPIDS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An enlisted man who earned a
Distinguished Service Cross in World War II has finally received
it, thanks to the prodding of a now-deceased Air Force colonel.
   ``It was 45 years ago they signed me up for that medal, but I
never received it _ until (a week ago) Wednesday,'' said Jim Bird,
67, a retired machinist.
   Retired Air Force Col. Fred Witzgall was researching Bird's Army
division and found Bird never received the medal he was awarded for
helping capture about 20 German soldiers on Dec. 26, 1944, in
Luxembourg.
   Witzgall sent Bird the necessary applications two years ago, and
Bird sent them on to the Army. By the time the medal arrived in the
mail, Bird couldn't thank the retired colonel. Witzgall died March
15.
   Bird said he doesn't reflect much on his service days.
   ``All that stuff tends to weigh you down after a while,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
