<FILEID>AP-NR-04-29-89 0720EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-WashingtonBicentennial     04-29 0427</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Washington Bicentennial,0436</SECOND>
<HEAD>George Bush to Honor Nation's First George at 200th Inaugural Anniversary</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN SHANAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Inaugurations have changed a bit since George
Washington became America's first president 200 years ago, as this
weekend's anniversary celebration of his swearing in will
demonstrate.
   An estimated 20,000 to 30,000 people witnessed the 1789
celebration, but more than 2 million people are expected to turn
out for the staged re-enactment of the inauguration, a fireworks
display, a 63-ship flotilla, a speech by President Bush and other
events Saturday and Sunday.
   Certainly the price tag has gone up. City officials estimate
police overtime and other costs to taxpayers will reach $3.5
million for the two days.
   Mayor Edward I. Koch said it was the biggest event to be held in
New York since the 1986 Statue of Liberty centennial.
   A parade of ships will kick off ceremonies Saturday afternoon.
Police Chief Robert J. Johnston Jr. estimated at least 2 million
people would line New York shorelines to see the vessels sail up
the Hudson River. A similar turnout is expected for the Saturday
night fireworks.
   The flotilla will include the aircraft carrier USS Forrestal,
which will exchange 13-gun salutes with Fort Hamilton in Brooklyn
just before noon. Then the USS Ticonderoga will lead the ships
through New York Harbor and up the Hudson to the George Washington
Bridge.
   Thirteen Navy ships will represent the 13 original Colonies.
They will be accompanied by 50 civilian ships representing the 50
states.
   The 22-minute pyrotechnics Saturday night will be choreographed
to the tune of ``Hail to the Chief.'' The fireworks will be set off
at 8:45 p.m. on the East River at the foot of Wall Street, where
Washington landed before his inauguration. The music and a
narration by Walter Cronkite will be broadcast over two local radio
stations.
   Sunday's events in lower Manhattan begin with an ecumenical
service at St. Paul's Chapel, where Washington prayed after his
swearing in. Afterward, Bush will participate in the dedication of
the new Museum of Constitutional Government in Federal Hall.
   Next comes the inauguration re-enactment at the hall, where
Washington took the oath of office on April 30, 1789, followed by
speech to the nation by Bush. Festivities conclude with a parade up
lower Broadway that repeats a procession of 200 years ago.
   Koch said in addition to the $3.5 million the city expects to
spend on police overtime, sanitation and other costs, another $2.6
million was raised by the private sector to pay for various
production expenses.
</TEXT>
