<FIRST>r a PM-ForcedLabor     04-29 0283</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Forced Labor,0294</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chinese Women Allegedly Forced Into Servitude</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHLEEN MACLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three young Chinese women lured to San
Francisco with a promise of dance lessons were kept in an apartment
and forced to perform domestic labor, authorities said.
   ``Basically, they were used to do domestic chores around the
residence. They could come and go, but it was a very structured
type of come and go,'' District Attorney chief investigator John
Majka said Friday, one day after authorities freed the women.
   The women _ ages 14, 19 and 20 _ had no money and no place to
go. They were placed in protective custody pending the outcome of
an the investigation, Majka said.
   One of the women had lived in the apartment for nearly a year.
   Police seized a large number of documents and other records at
the apartment and workplace of the homeowner, who police identified
only as a Chinese man. The documents were written in various
Chinese dialects and may take some time to evaluate, Majka said.
   No charges have been filed yet.
   The women were apparently lured from China with a promise of
studying dance at a fictitious school called the San Francisco
College of Music and Theater Arts.
   ``All of the girls appeared to be in generally good physical
condition. They were very happy and they thanked the investigators
for taking them out,'' Majka said. ``We believe they may have been
held against their will there.''
   Immigration and Naturalization Service officials said they were
unsure of the women's immigration status and were investigating it.
   The District Attorney's office received a letter earlier this
month suggesting they investigate the women's living situation.
</TEXT>
