<FILEID>AP-NR-04-29-89 0740EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-WashingtonBicentennial     04-29 0424</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Washington Bicentennial,0437</SECOND>
<HEAD>New York Prepares For Another Big Bash</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL STIEG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Organizers ordered up a flotilla of ships and a
fireworks extravaganza for today's 200th anniversary celebration of
George Washington's inauguration.
   Up to a million people were expected to view tonight's harbor
display, and hundreds of thousands were expected to attend Sunday's
reenactment and parade featuring President Bush and a stand-in
representing George Washington.
   ``It'll be George to George that day,'' said Wayne Baruch of
Radio City Music Hall Productions, which is producing the weekend's
events.
   ``Two centuries of the presidency is one of the great success
stories in human history. What we're celebrating is the enduring
strength and leadership of the presidency.''
   Today's celebration was to begin with a flotilla of ships up the
harbor.
   The fireworks display will be the city's second largest ever
after the Statue of Liberty show of 1986, but will outshine even
that show in some regards, organizers said.
   ``It should be more exciting than Liberty Weekend because people
will see a lot of special effects,'' said Donna Grucci, vice
president of Fireworks by Grucci, which is handling the
pyrotechnics.
   Ms. Grucci said the show will include the Grucci Split Comet,
``a golden weeping willow that crosses and crackles at the tips,''
magnesium blasts ``which will turn the night into day,'' and
humbler multi-colored low-level fountains ``like they had 200 years
ago.''
   The fireworks will be timed to coincide with band music and the
mellifluous tones of Walter Cronkite, who will be narrating the
show called ``Hail to the Chief.''
   On Sunday, the celebration becomes more serious as the incumbent
presidential George joins a George Washington stand-in for a
reenactment of the first inauguration.
   The reenactment at Federal Hall in lower Manhattan will resemble
the 1789 original, if you ignore the large-screen TV alongside the
platform. It will be followed by a parade through town with modern
military bands and 18th century-style fife and drum corps.
   The Designated George is William Sommerfield, a gray-haired
Philadelphian who looks and acts the part of Washington.
   ``People don't realize that every 50 years there's been a huge
celebration of the inauguration in New York City,'' said Wayne
Baruch of Radio City Music Hall Productions, which is producing the
weekend's events. ``This is the fourth one.''
   On Friday, there was a smattering of events up and down
Manhattan, from a scholarly symposium on Washington at the Fraunces
Tavern Museum downtown to a ceremony on the 100-year-old Washington
Bridge over the Harlem River.
</TEXT>
