<FIRST>r i PM-Japan-Politics 1stLd-Writethru   04-29 0493</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Politics, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0436,0503</SECOND>
<HEAD>Precede TOKYO</HEAD>
<HEAD>Takeshita Begins Southeast Asia Tour, Search For Successor Continues</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs to UPDATE with Takeshita's comments, arrival
in Thailand. Pickup 5th pvs, ``Takeshita said...''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita of
Japan arrived in Thailand today to begin a nine-day trip through
Southeast Asia while his political party tried to select his
successor back home.
   Takeshita, who says he will resign soon because of his
involvement in a stock-profiteering scandal, was greeted at
Bangkok's International Airport by his Thai counterpart, Chatichai
Choonhavan.
   Takeshita also is to visit Singapore, Malaysia, Indonesia and
the Philippines, which together with Thailand and Brunei form the
Association of Southeast Asian Nations. Japan has strong ties to
the group.
   ``On this current trip, I hope to further deepen and broaden
Japan's relations with ASEAN as well as our bilateral relations
with the individual ASEAN countries,'' Takeshita said in an arrival
statement. He said cooperative relations between Japan and Thailand
had grown by ``leaps and bounds.''
   Back home, Japan's governing Liberal Democratic Party continued
to work on finding a successor for Takeshita, who announced Tuesday
he would resign.
   News reports suggest the party may name former Foreign Minister
Masayoshi Ito, 75, as the new prime minister. Ito has said his age
and health problems with diabetes should disqualify him, but many
believe he would accept if asked.
   Takeshita said he was going ahead with the trip to Asia to
``maintain continuity'' in Japan's foreign policy. Developing
countries in Southeast Asia have been pressing Japan for economic
aid.
   The daily newspaper Asahi Shimbun said today that Takeshita and
his Cabinet probably would resign around May 20, a week before the
deadline for the upper house of parliament to approve the nation's
1989 budget.
   The governing party forced the $445 billion spending plan
through the powerful lower house Friday without bothering to try to
reach a consensus, a move condemned by the opposition, which has
boycotted parliament.
   In 35 years of unbroken rule, the Liberal Democrats had never
completely ignored the opposition in voting on the budget despite
its majority.
   A newspaper poll published today indicated that for the first
time in nine years more Japanese support the opposition parties
than the Liberal Democratic Party. In the poll, conducted by Asahi
Shimbun, 44 percent of 2,403 respondents said they supported one of
Japan's five main opposition parties or other minor parties, while
42 percent said they supported the Liberal Democrats.
   The poll was taken after Takeshita announced his resignation
plans. His popularity had dropped sharply as details of the stock
scandal surfaced.
   In the scandal, Recruit Co., an information services
conglomerate, sold unlisted stocks at low prices to about 160
prominent people, including politicians and businessmen. Many of
the recipients sold their shares after they were listed publicly
and rose sharply in value.
   Takeshita has admitted receiving more than $1 million in
political donations from Recruit in 1985-87.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
