<FIRST>u i PM-RedSea-OilSpill     04-29 0471</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Red Sea-Oil Spill,0480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Indian Oil Tanker Refloated, Pollution Damage Assessed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Indian supertanker that ran aground in
the Red Sea was refloated today after it spilled nearly 1 million
gallons of oil, sources said. An expert warned the oil could harm
fragile coral reefs and turtle breeding areas.
   Oil industry sources in Riyadh, the Saudi capital, said leakage
from the tanker Kanchenjunga apparently was less than had been
previously reported. A 50-mile long oil slick was breaking up, the
British Broadcasting Corp. said.
   The Saudi-based sources, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said an estimated 949,000 gallons of oil flowed from ruptured tanks
of the Kanchenjunga after it struck a reef near the port of Jiddah
on Wednesday.
   That spill was about 2 percent of the oil aboard the 276,744-ton
tanker, and about 8 percent of the 10 million gallons lost in the
Exxon Valdez accident in Alaska last month. Earlier, Lloyds
Shipping Intelligence Unit in London reported that 1.5 million
gallons had spilled in the Red Sea incident.
   While fears of a major pollution threat to the Red Sea eased,
one environmental expert warned that even a limited spillage could
be dangerous to the waterway's environment.
   ``The Red Sea is especially vulnerable because it has many
beautiful coral reefs, and there are some turtle breeding islands
in the area,'' said Walter Vreeland, an American advisor to the
Bahrain government on environmental problems. Vreeland also said
light crude oil, such as that carried by the Kanchenjunga, is more
toxic to marine life than heavier grades.
   Salvage industry sources said the state-owned Kanchenjunga,
believed to be India's biggest tanker, was refloated after some
cargo was pumped into another vessel, and later was taken to a
port. The cargo was to be reloaded later.
   The ship loaded about 1 million barrels of Iraqi ``Basra light''
crude at Saudi Arabia's Yanbu terminal and was bound for Bombay
when it hit the reef six miles off Jiddah. There were no injuries
reported among the crew of about 70.
   Jiddah port officials, Saudi Aramco, the national oil company,
and the Meterorological and Environmental Protection Authority, a
government agency, were jointly handling the case.
   In New Delhi, officials at the Shipping Corporation of India,
which owns the tanker, could not be reached for comment. Today was
a government holiday.
   Lloyds, which monitors shipping activities around the world,
reported on Friday that three of the ship's tanks, containing
nearly 200,000 barrels of oil, had been damaged.
   The Kanchenjunga has previously encountered trouble in the
Middle East as one of the first ships attacked in the Persian
Gulf's ``tanker war'' between Iraq and Iran. The bridge was wrecked
and two crew members were wounded in an attack by Iranian warplanes
in the Persian Gulf on Christmas Day, 1984.
</TEXT>
