<FIRST>u i PM-Lebanon     04-29 0323</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon,0336</SECOND>
<HEAD>Moslem Gunners Shell Christian Enclave Despite Cease-Fire</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Moslem gunners today lobbed shells into
Lebanon's Christian enclave in violation of a cease-fire called by
the Arab League.
   Six howitzer shells slammed into the Christian-controlled
coastal strip north of Beirut over five hours, a police spokesman
said. There was no response from army commander Gen. Michel Aoun's
Christian gunners, he said.
   Police said no casualties were reported from the sporadic
shelling.
   At least 273 people have died and 993 have been wounded in six
weeks of fierce fighting, the latest outbreak of Lebanon's 14-year
civil war.
   The spokesman, who requested anonymity, said the intermittent
shelling underscored differences over terms of the cease-fire,
which took effect Friday.
   He predicted the Syrians and their Druse allies would continue
fighting until Aoun lifts a blockade of ports they have been
operating illegally.
   If the shelling continues, the spokesman said, ``It could lead
to an exchange of fire and, consequently, it would shatter the
truce.''
   After Aoun imposed the blockades, the Syrians and their allies
laid siege to the 310-square mile enclave where 1 million
Christians live.
   Although he agreed to the cease-fire, Aoun disagrees with a
provision of the cease-fire that calls for ``lifting the blockades
imposed on all sea, air and land facilities.'' Aoun, who also heads
the Christian cabinet in Lebanon's dual government, interpreted the
clause to mean that a Moslem blockade of two ports in the Christian
enclave should be raised.
   Arab League Secretary General Chedli Klibi, in cables sent late
Friday to Aoun and his Sunni Moslem rival, clarified that the
accord covered ``all sea ports irrespective of their status.''
   But the Christian leader cabled back that his blockade of the
militia-run ports was enforced ``in implementation of Lebanese
laws.''
   The half-dozen illegal ports along Lebanon's Mediterranean
coastline were stripping the state treasury of $100 million a year
in uncollected taxes.
</TEXT>
