<FILEID>AP-NR-04-29-89 1012EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Britain-D-Day 1stLd-Writethru   04-29 0495</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-D-Day, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0467,0505</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vets Remember Americans Who Died In World War II Training Excercise</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 2 grafs to CORRECT month of accident to April, sted
June. Pickup 3rd pvs, `The soldiers...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TORCROSS, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. flags flew at half staff and 14
American war veterans bowed their heads in memory of 749 comrades
killed by German torpedo boats as they trained for the D-Day
invasion.
   The service, which took place next to a Sherman tank salvaged
from the shallows off Slapton Sands in Devon, ended a day of
tribute Friday to the American servicemen who died on April 28,
1944.
   The soldiers had been preparing amphibious landings as training
for the June 6 D-Day invasion of Normandy that summer.
   However, the training exercise turned into real battle when nine
enemy vessels chanced upon the 30,000 American troops in the
English Channel and torpedoed three of their landing craft.
   Earlier Friday, the 14 U.S. veterans boarded the British
destroyer HMS Bristol to lay a wreath on the sea off the southwest
coast of England. Many wept, hugging their wives, as they paid
their respects.
   The massacre was hushed up at the time to preserve morale in the
tense weeks before D-Day. After the war, it remained secret until
Ken Small, a local innkeeper, began investigating why so many
American servicemen's possessions kept washing up on the beach.
   Small recovered the Sherman tank in 1984 and persuaded local
authorities to turn it into a permanent memorial. His efforts led
to the dead Americans finally being officially honored at a
ceremony in 1987.
   As the wreath was thrown to the waves, a guard of honor stood to
attention on the destroyer's deck and two buglers of the Royal
Marines played ``Taps.''
   John Doyle, 72, of Missoula, Mont., who was captain of Landing
Ship Tank-515 which picked up many of the survivors, said he was
touched by the ceremony.
   ``We picked up about 100 survivors in the morning and of course
there was a lot of confusion, but this ceremony means a lot to all
of us 45 years on. I feel the people who died can now properly be
laid to rest,'' he said.
   His thoughts were echoed by other veterans who survived the
disaster.
   John Fedyszyn, 62, of Dunkirk, N.Y., was on LST-507 when a huge
explosion rocked the ship.
   ``I was in these waters for six hours until we were spotted and
picked up and I was only 17 at the time,'' he said. ``It is great
to be back but it's very emotional and I am a little tearful. It's
something I will never forget.''
   For 64-year-old Kenneth Bloch of Hicksville, N.Y., the day
marked the end of a long quest.
   ``When I was rescued from the sea, the first thing I noticed was
seeing my shipmates lying on the deck dead. For me, this is my way
of paying my tribute to all my friends,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
