<FIRST>r a PM-SpacePolicy 1stLd-Writethru a0451 04-29 0536</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Space Policy, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0451,0547</SECOND>
<HEAD>NASA Needs Long-Term Space Policy, Ex-Astronauts, Former Agency Officials
Say</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 13th graf, `Allen said...', to restore dropped first reference
to ex-astronaut Joseph Allen.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Space Shuttle, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARTHUR H. ROTSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SCOTTSDALE, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly 20 years after man landed on the
moon, the U.S. space program lacks clear long-range goals and
public commitment, former astronauts and NASA officials said.
   ``We need a consistent government policy,'' former space agency
administrator James M. Beggs said Friday.
   Andrew J. Stofan, a vice president of Martin Marietta's
Astronautics Group and former NASA official, said the agency should
have a strategic plan to colonize the planet Mars over the next 100
years. A manned space station would be a first step toward that
end, he said.
   Beggs and Stofan were among a panel of experts who discussed the
space program at an annual news conference of the Aviation-Space
Writers Association.
   Also at the meeting, the head of a national project to build a
spacecraft that can take off and land like an airplane, said the
plan was making great progress but proposed cuts in defense
spending were endangering it.
   ``We look at it as the opening of a new era, the era of
hypersonics,'' said Robert Barthelemy, head of the National
Aero-Space Plane project.
   The craft would be capable of horizontal takeoff and landing
from Earth to orbit, traveling at speeds of up to 17,000 miles per
hour.
   Japan, West Germany, France, the Soviet Union and Great Britain
all are working on their own hypersonic programs, Barthelemy said.
``Maybe you need a world consortium to do this,'' he added.
   Beggs said those countries also are looking at a manned space
station and eventually exploring Mars.
   ``But our leadership is no longer guaranteed. We must earn it,''
he said.
   Former astronaut Charles ``Pete'' Conrad Jr. said the
administrator of the National Aeronautics and Space Administration
should have Cabinet-level status as a secretary of space.
   Stofan said a lack of direction, long-range vision and firm
budgets have led the space agency to waste billions of dollars on
projects planned, then cut back, then planned again with nothing
accomplished.
   Another former astronaut, Joseph Allen, said several space
accomplishments were imminent. He noted the launch of the Magellan
space probe to the planet Venus from the shuttle Atlantis, which
was delayed Friday at least until next week, and the planned launch
of a Mars probe from the shuttle late this year.
   But he said it is increasingly apparent that many projects, and
particularly a manned space station, have proceeded too slowly
because of ``a lack of focused leadership.''
   `In many ways, we're not being honest to the generations to come
because of this lack of commitment and lack of a strategic plan,''
said Allen.
   Conrad said that the Apollo Applications Group recommended more
than 20 years ago that a manned space station be built and followed
by a mission to Mars. But successive presidents shot the
recommendations down.
   They were among a set of recommendations made again last year by
the National Commission on Space.
   ``It's now 1989 and the space station is about seven years
away,'' said Allen.
</TEXT>
