<FIRST>r i PM-Sweden-EmergencyLanding 1stLd-Writethru   04-29 0207</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sweden-Emergency Landing, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0442,0208</SECOND>
<HEAD>Airliner Makes Emergency Landing, But No Fire Found In Engine</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with mechanics discovering that cockpit
light falsely warned engine was on fire. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A British Boeing 737 carrying 103
people made an emergency landing in Goteborg after a warning light
indicated one of its engines caught fire shortly after takeoff, an
airport official said today.
   After the plane landed safely, the crew discovered the warning
light had malfunctioned and there was no fire in one of the right
engines.
   The pilot of the Air UK Leisure Ltd. airliner reported the fire
moments after departing from Helsinki, Finland, for London, said Bo
Hansson, an official at the airport in Goteborg, 280 miles
southwest of Stockholm.
   The crew activated fire extinguishers in the engine, but the
warning light remained on, Hansson said.
   ``The pilot demanded permission to land at the nearest airfield,
which was Landvetter in Goteborg,'' he said. ``The landing was
successful and the passengers were never exposed to any danger.''
   Mechanics found nothing wrong with the aircraft's engine,
refilled its fire extinguishers, and the aircraft later resumed its
flight to London with its 95 passengers and eight-member crew,
Hansson said.
</TEXT>
