<FIRST>r i AM-Bermuda-DeathPenalty     04-29 0271</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bermuda-Death Penalty,0278</SECOND>
<HEAD>Voters May Decide Death Penalty Abolition</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HAMILTON, Bermuda (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawmakers on this popular resort island
have decided to keep the death penalty for now, but residents
eventually may have the final say.
   The House of Assenbly voted 19-19 to retain capital punishment
for premeditated murder, with the speaker of the house casting the
deciding vote in favor.
   Despite the vote, the governing United Bermuda Party of Premier
John Swan is still considering whether to put the matter to a
national referendum. Britain, of which Bermuda is a colony,
abolished the death penalty in 1965.
   ``We will now discuss the matter in the party caucus,'' Swan
said after Friday's vote. ``We feel the public should have a say
before any moves for abolition.''
   Swan raised the possibility of a referendum on March 31, 10 days
after Bermuda's governor, Sir Desmond Langley, stayed the hanging
of Troy Dean Shorter.
   Shorter was convicted of first-degree murder in the slaying of
shopkeeper Roger Redman. He had exhausted all appeals when Langley
exercised his right to commute death sentences to terms of life
imprisonment.
   The stay of execution was strongly protested.
   The legislative debate over capital punishment also has delayed
the opening of another murder trial, that of 29-year-old
businessman Leroy Alvin Dunlop. Dunlop is accused of the July 10
slayings of his girlfriend and her two daughters.
   Bermuda uses hanging to execute murderers. The last time the
gallows were used was Dec. 2, 1977, when murderers Larry Tacklyn
and Buck Burrows were hanged.
   The double hanging led to widespread civil unrest and the
arrival of British troops to quell riots.
</TEXT>
