<FIRST>r i AM-StadiumDisaster     04-29 0417</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Stadium Disaster,0428</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mourners Sing ``You'll Never Walk Alone'' For 95 Soccer Victims</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIVERPOOL, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of mourners sang the
Liverpool soccer team's anthem, ``You'll Never Walk Alone,'' and
lit 95 candles during a memorial service Saturday for fans who died
in Britain's worst sporting tragedy.
   Liverpool's Anglican cathedral was decorated with a huge
Liverpool banner and wreaths in the team's red and white colors as
this soccer-mad city paid its final tribute to the 95 fans trampled
or crushed to death at an April 15 match. Prime Minister Margaret
Thatcher, the Duke and Duchess of Kent, politicians, soccer
officials and Liverpool players joined members of bereaved families
and 450 injured fans at the hour-long service, attended by about
2,000 people.
   Outside the cathedral, about 800 people watched on a giant TV
screen. Millions watched the nationally televised service at home.
   A choir of young boys sang as white candles were lit for each of
the 95 victims who died at Hillsborough stadium in Sheffield during
a Football Association Cup semifinal. A red remembrance book with
their names was placed on the altar.
   ``They went to see a match on a bright spring day, never
dreaming they were to enter the valley of the shadow of death,''
the Rev. Dr. John Newton said in the sermon.
   He pleaded for greater safety for soccer fans.
   ``Please God, a new pattern of football, safe for all
spectators, will be part of their memorial too,'' he said.
   There were prayers and blessings from Liverpool clergy,
Archbishop of York John Habgood and finally Cardinal Basil Hume,
the Archbishop of Westminster, after which the congregation fell
silent.
   The silence was broken by the soprano voice of 12-year-old
Martin Polglaise, a Liverpool fan and choirboy, singing ``You'll
Never Walk Alone,'' which Liverpool supporters have sung for three
decades to inspire the players to victory.
   The congregation rose, joining in the refrain, many wiping tears
from their eyes.
   The dignitaries then filed outside where the Dean of Liverpool,
the Very Rev. Derrick Walters, hallowed the Hillsborough Memorial
Stone, set in the pavement just in front of the cathedral. Made of
red sandstone, its gold inscription reads: ``Hillsborough, April
15, 1989, You'll Never Walk Alone.''
   Wreaths were laid by the prime minister, the Duke and Duchess of
Kent, and other political and civic leaders. Queen Elizabeth II,
who was criticized by some local officials for not attending, sent
a wreath and a message of sympathy that was printed inside the
service program.
</TEXT>
