<FILEID>AP-NR-04-29-89 1308EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Lebanon     04-29 0530</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon,0546</SECOND>
<HEAD>Moslems Fire On Christian Heartland, Violating Truce</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Moslem forces fired howitzer shells into
the Christian heartland on Saturday, violating the latest truce
called by the Arab League.
   Police said Syrian and allied Druse gunners fired a half dozen
shells into the coastal strip of the 310-square-mile enclave north
of Beirut. No casualties were reported.
   A police spokesman said the forces of Gen. Michel Aoun,
commander of the Christian army brigades, did not retaliate.
   The sporadic shelling came during growing differences betweeen
Aoun and the Arab League over the interpretation of a key provision
in the truce accord that went into effect at noon Friday.
   The truce is the fourth effort by the Arab League in less than a
month to contain six weeks of hostilities that have killed 273
people and wounded nearly 1,000.
   A provision in the agreement calls for ``lifting the blockades
imposed on all sea, land and air facilities...''
   Aoun, who also heads the Christian Cabinet in Lebanon's dual
government, insists that the clause covers only the ports of Beirut
and Jounieh in the Christian enclave. They are besieged by the
Syrians and allied forces.
   Arab League Secretary-General Chedli Klibi sent cables to Aoun
and his Sunni Moslem rival, Salim Hoss, saying the provision in
question covered ``all sea ports.''
   Aoun responded to Klibi in a cable saying his blockade of
militia-run ports was ``in implementation of Lebanese laws and
therefore are not to be described as blockades.''
   ``Lebanon has sought the support of the Arab League to help it
implement its laws and extend its authority on all its territory
and not to give a legitimate status with an Arab cover to
illegitimate situations (ports) that violate local and
international laws,'' Aoun's cable added.
   The Syrians and their allies besieged the Christian enclave in
retaliation for a blockade by Aoun's forces of militia-run ports.
   Aoun, on March 6, ordered the blockade to stop the illegal ports
from collecting customs fees that instead would go to the state
treasury.
   Aoun has charged that three ports run by Syrian-backed militias
along the Mediterranean coast south of Beirut were used to
``smuggle drugs and terrorism to the world.''
   Hoss sent a cable to Klibi declaring support for his
interpretation of the controversial provision and saying the
majority of the Lebanese people did not regard Aoun as their
legitimate prime minister.
   An aide to Hoss, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the
dispute might ``block implementation of the truce'' which was
announced late Thursday after an emergency meeting of the Arab
foreign ministers in Tunisia.
   Aoun had welcomed the Arab League's decision to send Arab
military observers to oversee implementation of the truce, calling
it ``a shy step in the right direction of lifting the Syrian
hegemony off Lebanon.''
   Aoun and other Christian leaders accuse the Syrians of failing
to achieve a 1976 peacekeeping mandate from the Arab League by
siding with the Moslems against the Christians in the civil strife.
   Aoun has declared a ``war of liberation'' to drive Syria's
40,000 troops from eastern and northern Lebanon as well as from
west and south Beirut.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
