<FILEID>AP-NR-04-29-89 1315EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-RedSeaSpill     04-29 0381</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Red Sea Spill,0392</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tanker Spills Nearly 1 Million Gallons Of Oil In Red Sea</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A supertanker that ran aground in the Red
Sea was refloated Saturday, but sources said it leaked nearly 1
million gallons of oil that could damage coral reefs and turtle
breeding grounds.
   Salvage crews were breaking up a 50-mile oil slick the Indian
tanker left after it ran aground off Saudi Arabia on Wednesday. The
accident ruptured three of the ship's tanks and sent about 2
percent of its cargo into the water, according to the company that
owns the vessel, Shipping Corp. of India.
   The tanker was taken Saturday to the Saudi port of Jiddah after
part of its cargo was pumped into another vessel so the tanker
could be refloated.
   Lloyd's Shipping Intelligence Unit in London reported earlier
that 1.5 million gallons had leaked, but Saudi-based sources who
requested anonymity said Saturday that about 924,000 gallons
spilled.
   The Exxon Valdez spilled about 10 million gallons of oil into
the water off Alaska last month.
   S. K. Sood, joint managing director of the Shipping Corp. of
India, said the 276,744-ton Kanchenjunga supertanker had 71 people
on board when the accident occurred six miles off Jiddah. There
were no reports of injuries.
   His statement _ issued by the government-run company in Bombay,
India _ did not give the cause of the accident, which occurred
after the tanker picked up a load of light crude and headed back
toward Bombay.
   Although earlier fears of a major pollution threat to the Red
Sea eased Saturday, one environmental expert warned that even a
relatively small spill could endanger the waterway's environment.
   ``The Red Sea is especially vulnerable because it has many
beautiful coral reefs, and there are some turtle breeding islands
in the area,'' said Walter Vreeland, an American advisor to Bahrain
on environmental problems. Vreeland also said light crude oil is
more toxic to marine life than heavier grades.
   The Kanchenjunga was one of the first ships attacked in the
Persian Gulf during the ``tanker war'' that once raged between Iraq
and Iran.
   The ship's bridge was wrecked and two crew members were wounded
in an attack by Iranian warplanes in the gulf on Christmas Day,
1984.
</TEXT>
