<FIRST>r i AM-Israel-SovietJews     04-29 0184</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Soviet Jews,0188</SECOND>
<HEAD>Record Yearly Number Of Invitations From Israel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet Jewish immigrants living in Israel have
submitted a record number of invitations for their relatives to
come from the Soviet Union, Israel radio reported Saturday.
   It said that about 79,000 invitations were submitted to Soviet
authorities last year, the highest annual figure since the
beginning of the mass Soviet Jewish emigration in the late 1960s.
   An invitation from relatives living abroad is a necessary step
for a person wishing to emigrate from the Soviet Union.
   Uri Gordon, head of the Jewish Agency's immigration department,
was quoted by the radio as estimating that Soviet Jewish emigration
would reach 50,000 this year.
   But the radio quoted Gordon as saying that 90 percent of the
emigrants are likely to choose the United States and other Western
countries instead of Israel.
   Last year, the Soviets allowed about 20,000 Jews to emigrate.
Only about 2,200 chose to settle in the Jewish state.
   In the first three months of 1989, 9,461 Jews were permitted to
leave, according to the Washington-based National Conference for
Soviet Jewry.
</TEXT>
