<SECOND>AM-People,0770</SECOND>
<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first person to win a new
trophy in jazz dubbed an ``Ella'' to honor lifetime achievement was
the award's namesake, Ella Fitzgerald.
   Miss Fitzgerald was honored at a black-tie party Friday night to
celebrate her 71st birthday, which was Tuesday. The gala was a
fund-raiser for the Society of Singers, an organization that helps
needy singers.
   Bill Cosby was chosen to serve as master of ceremonies and among
those who had planned to attend were Dionne Warwick, the Pointer
Sisters, Mel Torme, the Manhattan Transfer and Carol Burnett.
   Saxophonist Benny Carter, who discovered Fitzgerald when she was
15, was scheduled to lead a jazz session.
