<NOTE>Eds: A version of the following item moved on sports wires.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BARCELONA, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Juan Antonio Samaranch, president of the
International Olympic Committee, landed in the hospital with a
bleeding ulcer after four days of meetings concerning the 1992
Barcelona Summer Olympic Games.
   A spokeswoman for the Quiron Clinic said Saturday that his
condition was good.
   Samaranch, 68, ``enjoyed a quiet, uneventful night and was
resting comfortably today,'' she said.
   His doctors indicated the ulcer was not serious and may have
resulted from excessive use of aspirin, she said.
   Samaranch was elected president of the IOC at the Moscow Summer
Olypmics in July 1980 and served as IOC vice president from
1974-78. He has been a member of the IOC since 1966.
   He is also the president of the Barcelona-based Caixa de
Pensiones savings association, one of Spain's largest financial
institutions.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For her ``Just Say No'' drug campaign, former
first lady Nancy Reagan was given the ``Pioneer of the Year'' award
by a U.S.-Soviet organization that fights drug abuse.
   ``This award recognizes Mrs. Reagan's invaluable global
contribution to substance abuse recovery and prevention,'' the Rev.
J.W. Canty said Friday.
   Canty, who presented the award to Mrs. Reagan in a closed
ceremony at her Century City office, is chairman of the Soviet-U.S.
Joint Conference on Alcoholism, Drug Addiction and Peace. The
Episcopal priest established the first Alcoholics Anonymous group
in Moscow, where he still works.
   Three Soviet members of the Moscow AA group told Mrs. Reagan
about their battle with alcoholism.
   The award, shaped in a structure of building blocks, symbolizes
the process of recovery from drug abuse, Canty said. He added that
Mrs. Reagan hoped to pay another visit to Moscow to aid in the
effort to combat alcohol and drug abuse.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Variety is the spice of an actor's life, says
Peter Boyle, whose easy transition from slapstick comedy to
hard-core drama has made him one of Hollywood's busier character
actors.
   ``It's fun to do a great number of roles _ doing the same thing
can get extremely boring,'' Boyle said last week.
   In the film comedy ``The Dream Team,'' Boyle plays an
advertising executive whose belief that he's really Jesus Christ
lands him in a psychiatric hospital. He also stars opposite John
Candy in the just-released car-chase film ``Speed Zone.''
   Boyle will be seen this week on television in the dramatic
miniseries ``Guts and Glory,'' about former White House aide Oliver
North's involvement in the Iran-Contra affair. Boyle plays former
national security adviser John Poindexter in the two-part show,
which begins Sunday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PIGEON FORGE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dolly Parton is launching a two-year,
$10 million expansion of her country theme park here in the
mountainous region where she was born.
   The plan will allow Dollywood to operate on a year-round basis
beginning in the spring of 1990, the entertainer announced Friday.
   The expansion includes shops, restaurants, a celebrity theater
and a new museum that's nearly double the size of the current one.
   Parton, 43, opened the park in 1986 near the Smoky Mountain
National Park in East Tennessee. The flamboyant singer grew up in
nearby Sevierville in a two-room mountain shack.
   ``I think it would be great for the business community here if
we could help make the Smokies a year-round resort area by doing
special things in the wintertime, because winter in the Smokies is
gorgeous and really pretty mild in terms of weather,'' she said in
a statement.
   Parton is celebrating her 25th year as an entertainer. She has
starred in several movies including the hit ``9 to 5,'' was host of
a television series, and recently released her 50th album, ``White
Limozeen.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
