<FIRST>r w AM-WorthBingham     04-29 0277</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Worth Bingham,260</SECOND>
<HEAD>For Release 6:30 p.m. EDT, time set by source</HEAD>
<HEAD>Journal-Constitution Team Wins Worth Bingham Prize</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Reporter Bill Dedman and five editors of The
Atlanta Journal-Constitution were named winners Saturday of the
1988 Worth Bingham Prize for ``The Color of Money,'' a series on
racial discrimination in lending practices of Atlanta banks and
savings and loan institutions.
   Dedman was designated recipient of the $2,500 cash award, but
the three judges said the honor would be shared by the team of
editors who, ``in the face of opposition and denials, put the
series in the paper.'' The prize was announced at the annual White
House Correspondents Association dinner.
   Among the editors cited were copy editor Sharon Bailey,
assistant city editor Hyde Post, and assistant managing editors
Dwight Morris and Wendell Rawls Jr. The judges also named Bill
Kovach, editor of the Atlanta papers when the series ran last year.
They said that Kovach, ``during the 22 months he was there, created
an environment where tough, probing journalism like `The Color of
Money' could be practiced, making the Atlanta newspapers worthy of
the legacy of Ralph McGill and Eugene C. Patterson.''
   Dedman, who now works for The Washington Post, ``reported the
series with determination and wrote it with accuracy and style,''
according to judges Howell Raines of The New York Times, Bob
Woodward of The Washington Post and Barbara Matusow of
Washingtonian magazine.
   The Worth Bingham prize, created after the death, in 1966, of
the 34-year-old scion of the Bingham newspaper family in
Louisville, Ky., honors newspaper or magazine reporting that
investigates situations of national significance where the public
interest is being ill-served.
</TEXT>
