<FIRST>r i AM-Afghanistan     04-29 0474</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan,0490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Claims 422 Rebels Surrender</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHARON HERBAUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government said Saturday that 422
Moslem guerrillas have agreed to stop fighting and give up their
weapons, bringing to 3,000 the number of rebels it claims have
surrendered.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Mohammad Nabi Amani refused to name
the groups or individuals who surrendered but said their numbers
have increased since Feb. 15, when the Soviet Union withdrew its
remaining troops from Afghanistan.
   ``We are expecting more in the future, maybe a major one very
soon,'' Amani said. He did not say when the 422 guerrillas
surrendered or what happened to them.
   The U.S.-backed rebels have been fighting since April 1978 to
overthrow the Marxist government of President Najib. There are no
reliable estimates on how many total guerrillas there are.
   The government also said it recently reached agreements with a
number of village leaders along the Salang Highway, the key supply
route between the capital and the Soviet border to the north.
   The agreements offered each village much-needed food and fuel,
provided that government vehicles were allowed to travel unmolested
on the highway. Rebels have consistently attacked government
vehicles on the road.
   The government said the offer, which was repeated in the
national press, was accepted by nearly every village. Only the
village of Mirbackhat was singled out for refusing.
   Amani also reported fighting had occurred in the provinces of
Nangahar, Kandahar, Herat and Paktia since Friday night.
   The spokesman said rebels fired rockets into the eastern city of
Jalalabad, the capital of Nangahar province. The city has been
under siege since March 6.
   Amani said 7,000 rebels have died in the Jalalabad assault,
while only 300 soldiers and civilians have been killed. Other
diplomats have put the government death toll at about 2,500.
   They say casualties among the civilians in Jalalabad have been
high, but they have not provided estimates.
   Jalalabad, 75 miles east of Kabul, once had a population of
64,000 but tens of thousands of people have fled to Kabul or into
Pakistan.
   Amani said three civilians were killed in the latest attack and
five were wounded. He said the Afghan armed forces fired heavy
artillery at the rebels, killing 117 and wounding 113.
   The Soviet news agency Tass also reported heavy shelling and
rocket attacks in Kabul, and said that four civilians were killed
and three wounded. It said Afghan aircraft and artillery
retaliated, ``putting out of action 230 rebels.'' It did not
elaborate.
   Tass also said that government forces found a ``considerable
amount'' of explosives at various locations in Kabul ``which
extremists intended to use against civilians.''
   In the town of Sarobi, between Kabul and Jalalabad, 16 rebels
were killed and 15 were injured others injured, Amani said.
   One civilian each died in Herat, Kandahar and Paktia provinces,
he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
