<FIRST>r i AM-Haiti     04-29 0244</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Haiti,0251</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rebel Soldiers Transferred To Provinces</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL NORTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ Military ruler Lt. Gen. Prosper
Avril broke up a mutinous military unit by transferring most of the
soldiers to provincial garrisons, independent Radio Metropole
reported Saturday.
   The powerful Dessalines Barracks Battalion rebelled April 2
after Avril discharged four of its officers who were implicated in
drug trafficking.
   Loyal troops put down the uprising, and unofficial reports say
at least 30 soldiers and civilians were killed and 75 wounded in
the fighting.
   About 590 of the Dessalines Barracks' 613 enlisted men who have
reported for duty in recent weeks boarded buses in front of army
headquarters and were driven to new military posts scattered across
the impoverished Caribbean nation, Radio Metropole said.
   The army high command has accepted the resignations of an
unspecified number of Dessalines soldiers, Radio Metropole said,
quoting army sources.
   Avril has forced out around 140 officers in his realignment of
the undisciplined 7,000-man army since he took power after
noncommissioned officers in the Presidential Guard overthrew Lt.
Gen. Henri Namphy on Sept. 17, 1988.
   Many of the discharged officers were suspected of being involved
in the shipment of cocaine from Colombia to the United States.
   Washington has made a crackdown on drug trafficking a condition
for restoring $70 million in Haitian aid. The aid was cut off after
elections planned for November 1987 were halted by gunmen aligned
with the ousted Duvalier dictatorship.
</TEXT>
