<FIRST>r i AM-Pope-Africa     04-29 0562</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pope-Africa,0577</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pope Tells Youths to Defend Social Justice</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEPHEN R. WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANTANANARIVO, Madagascar (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II on Saturday
urged 20,000 youths at a soccer stadium to reject violence and
embrace forgiveness and reconciliation in this troubled African
island nation.
   On the first full day of his nine-day African tour, the pope
made frequent reference to the social and economic problems that
contributed to recent anti-government riots in Madagascar in which
six people were killed.
   After flying to the port of Antsiranana on the northern tip of
the island for a outdoor Mass, the pope returned to the capital to
address youths at the Alarobia stadium, a soccer ground cut into a
red hillside.
   ``Whoever you are, whatever your difficulties, you have to be
intransigent in the defense of rights and justice,'' John Paul
said, speaking in French while standing on a raised platform.
``Reject violence, reject contempt, reject lies and dishonesty.
Take risks if it's necessary, but ... know how to forgive and
reconcile.''
   In a speech to the country's 21 bishops later, the pope praised
their recent document proposing natural family planning to control
the country's 3 percent annual population growth.
   ``You refuse `contraceptive imperialism' and even more abortion,
which is against Malagasy wisdom and civil law,'' the pope said.
``I strongly encourage you to continue to educate consciences on
this essential point.''
   Only one in 100 married women in Madagascar uses contraception,
according to the World Watch Institute. The population of 11
million is projected to approach 17 million by 2000.
   In the meeting with youths, the pope cited the concerns of
students and laborers who can't find jobs or salaries that allow
them to raise a family. He singled out rural workers who ``often
are subjected to a climate of insecurity and violent actions,'' an
apparent reference to the widespread banditry in the countryside.
   One student asked the pope if he had any remedies for the
country's ``critical situation of decay.''
   ``Let's say clearly that it is not my position to analyze all
the aspects, nor to propose solutions. First and foremost because
it's you, the Malagasy people, who have to act,'' the pope said.
   The Roman Catholic Church in Madagascar has often spoken out
against the policies of President Didier Ratsiraka, saying the
country has slipped into moral, social and economic decay.
   Ratsiraka, who took power in 1975, was re-elected last month to
a third seven-year term. Opposition leaders charged the elections
were rigged.
   Opposition parties have suspended their protests during the
pope's visit, declaring a ``papal truce.'' Two main opposition
leaders have asked to meet with the pope, but Vatican officials
said a meeting was uncertain.
   The youths clapped, waved banners and swayed to the rhythm of
Polynesian-flavored music reflecting the diverse ethnic makeup of
the country. Young girls on a platform held up cards forming words
in Malagasy, including the slogan ``Everyone must work together to
improve our country.''
   The pope urged the youths to reject drugs, alcohol and casual
sex, saying, ``Casual encounters are but a caricature of love.''
   In Antisaranana, the pope celebrated Mass for about 20,000
people gathered on a dirt and sand field next to the airport.
   The pope leaves Monday for the tiny French Indian Ocean island
of Reunion, then travels to Zambia and Malawi before returning to
Rome on May 6.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890429-0082 </DOCNO>
