<FIRST>r w AM-HHS-Abortion 1stLd-Writethru a0504 04-29 0826</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-HHS-Abortion, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0504,800</SECOND>
<HEAD>EDs: SUBs 14th graf to CORRECT that meeting set for this week sted
next, pick up 15th graf: ``That would be ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Health and Human Services Secretary Louis
Sullivan is engaged in an intense, behind-the-scenes effort to name
an Oklahoma state official to a top agency job, threatening trouble
with anti-abortion forces.
   ``I can't think of anything in the short-term more likely to
cause a real uproar,'' said Gary Bauer, president of the Family
Research Council and a former aide in the Reagan White House.
   Sullivan's choice to head the Family Services Administration,
which manages major welfare programs, is Oklahoma state Secretary
of Social Services Robert Fulton.
   Resistance to Fulton marks the first clash between Sullivan and
anti-abortion forces since a truce in the first days of the Bush
administration that assured pro-lifers they would get top agency
posts. They in turn vowed not to oppose Sullivan's confirmation.
   Sen. Gordon Humphrey, R-N.H., said that while ``the
administration has shown compete good faith'' on the earlier
appointments, the controversy around Fulton adds ``a whole new
element.''
   Even though Fulton would be heading a non-medical agency, he
would be ``dealing with family matters,'' Humphrey said last week.
   Sullivan first upset anti-abortion activists with a newspaper
interview indicating he personally opposed abortion but favored
women's right to choose.
   In the fray that followed, Sullivan assured his critics that he
shared Bush's opposition to abortion except in cases of rape,
incest or danger to the mother's life.
   Humphrey and other conservatives in Congress sought assurances
from the White House that several top HHS jobs sensitive to
abortion policy would go to people who actively shared Bush's
anti-abortion views.
   The positions for which they sought assurances were
undersecretary, assistant secretary for health and assistant
secretary for public affairs, Humphrey said, and the lawmakers
suggested names for Sullivan to consider.
   One of the first people Sullivan recommended for an HHS position
was among those suggested. James O. Mason, formerly director of the
Centers for Disease Control in Atlanta, has been confirmed by the
Senate as assistant secretary for health, a position that will have
policy dealings on the abortion issue.
   Two others Sullivan recommended early on also were applauded by
the conservative Republican lawmakers: Constance Horner, director
of the Office of Personnel Management, whose nomination to be
undersecretary is awaiting Senate confirmation; and Kay James,
former spokeswoman for the National Right to Life Committee, as
assistant secretary for public affairs.
   Despite the latest controversy, Sullivan has persisted in
support of Fulton. And Oklahoma Gov. Henry Bellmon has lobbied on
Fulton's behalf at the White House, according to sources who spoke
on the condition of anonymity.
   Sullivan is to meet with White House officials to discuss his
recommendation this week, said Chase Untermeyer, assistant to the
president for personnel. Untermeyer said that while Fulton is
Sullivan's choice, ``there are also other candidates we are looking
at.''
   ``That would be a very controversial nomination if they went
forward with it,'' said Douglas Johnson, legislative director of
the National Right to Life Committee.
   In a letter to the White House, Humphrey said he was concerned
about allegations in a lawsuit suggesting that from 1977 to 1983 a
number of babies born with spina bifida _ a severe spinal defect _
were denied needed surgery in a state-operated hospital in Oklahoma.
   Fulton, who in 1983 became director a state agency with
authority over the hospital, strongly denies any suggestion that he
condoned such practices. He recently was dropped as a defendant in
the lawsuit.
   ``It's certainly not true that we sat around and let the
challenged practices continue,'' he said in an interview. ``There
isn't any question we took appropriate action.''
   The lawsuit was filed in October 1985 after Fulton refused to
sign a consent decree, which he said would have been tantamount to
an admission of guilt on the state's part to things he knew not to
be true.
   He said that while he served in the two top state health
offices, only one spina bifida infant died and that child died of
complications from multiple birth defects.
   Humphrey said, however, that he remains concerned about the
``very serious allegations, which if true would certainly seem to
rule him out from a place in Health and Human Services since his
point of view would be directly in conflict with that of the
president in the area of right to life.''
   Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, one of the conservative senators who
initially expressed concern about Sullivan, said in a recent
interview that the secretary and President Bush have been sensitive
to abortion opponents' concerns.
   Hatch said he is satisfied with those Sullivan has recommended
to top HHS positions, adding, ``but I don't think the abortion
issue should drive everything. I think it's also important that you
get the best people you can get and I think they're moving in that
direction.''
</TEXT>
