<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     04-29 0443</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0458</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GAINESVILLE, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chandelle Summer, an attorney who
concentrates on criminal defense law, wants to go up in court
against her husband, an assistant prosecutor.
   Her husband's boss doesn't want that to happen, she said, so
she's taking him to court.
   Mrs. Summer said Andy Fuller, district attorney for the
Northeastern Circuit Superior Court, told her he will not let her
husband, Assistant District Attorney Dan Summer, represent the
state in cases in which she represents the defendant.
   In a petition filed with the U.S. District Court in Gainesville,
Mrs. Summer said Fuller's ``vacillating policy'' regarding the
couple's professional dealings ``has caused confusion and delay.''
   She claims that Fuller's action violates her rights to due
process and equal protection guaranteed by the 14th Amendment.
Fuller declined to comment on the petition.
   Mrs. Summer said she is not seeking monetary damages. She simply
wants a ruling by a federal judge that will allow her to deal with
her husband as she deals with other district attorneys.
   ``I just want to be treated just like everyone else who is
practicing law and does criminal defense law. I don't want to have
any advantages or disadvantages,'' she said.
   Said her husband: ``It's a free country.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>GLENDALE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The principal of Cerritos Elementary
School is serious about higher education. That's why Jeannie Flint
spent a day on the roof.
   Mrs. Flint, 43, made good on a wager with her students. If all
400 read for 500,000 minutes at home, she would become the
educator-on-the-roof.
   The pupils did it, averaging 1,250 minutes of reading or more
than 20 hours each. So as students serenaded her Friday with ``Up
On The Roof,'' the principal climbed two ladders and perched on the
roof complete with parasol, balloon-bedecked chair, desk, cordless
phone and books.
   She is not the first to pull such a stunt. A San Gabriel school
principal donned a monkey costume and spent the day on the
cafeteria for 1 million minutes of outside reading. A South
Pasadena principal was ``roofed'' twice for good reading quotas.
   At Cerritos Elementary School, parents were asked to keep track
of their children's reading or to read to the kids themselves.
Another incentive came from the local Kiwanis Club, which promised
a $50 U.S. savings bond to one student from each grade who read the
most.
   ``I want to encourage them to read and make reading a lifelong
habit,'' Mrs. Flint said as a lunch prepared by students was
hoisted up to her on the flat-topped roof. ``I knew they could do
it. I just didn't think they could do it so soon.''
</TEXT>
