<FIRST>r a AM-MissingWinners     04-29 0448</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Missing Winners,0456</SECOND>
<HEAD>Six Tickets Still Out In Pennsylvania Lottery Prize</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICH KIRKPATRICK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIDDLETOWN, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Six winning ticket holders for the $115.5
million jackpot still had not come forward when Super 7 officials
closed their offices for the weekend. The missing numbers are worth
$8.3 million each.
   Eight of 14 possible winning tickets from Wednesday's
headline-grabbing jackpot had been turned in. The thrill of instant
wealth attracted interest from as far away as New Zealand, lottery
officials said Friday.
   ``Ticket sales were spread around,'' said George Andersen,
lottery deputy executive director. ``We hope everyone checks their
tickets and we get a full set of winners.''
   Each of the 14 jackpot-winning tickets is worth $8.3 million
over the next 26 years. The annual payment, before any taxes, is
$317,524.67 for each ticket. The first payments will be handed out
in two weeks, at the local retail outlets where the tickets were
purchased and after completion of an extensive computerized
validation process, said lottery spokesman Terry Murphy.
   Consolation winners learned Friday night that matching six
numbers in the April 26 drawing paid $4,842.50 and five numbers
paid $275.36. Jackpot tickets matched seven of the 11 numbers drawn.
   Winners have a year from the date of the drawing to turn in
their tickets, or the money returns to the Lottery Fund and is lost
to the winner. About 1 percent of all the big prizes go unclaimed,
lottery officials said.
   Winners are given an extensive counseling session, with advice
on financial planning, consulting an attorney, estate planning,
explanation of the annuity from which the prize is drawn over the
26-year payout, and how to handle the media.
   ``We tell them to face the media, tell the truth, be as open as
they wish and if they don't wish to answer a personal question,
they need not do it,'' Andersen said. ``Typically, they're real
good at it.
   ``Because many of them are in a whirlwind of shock and surprise,
we have all this prepared in a folder and hand it to them,''
Andersen said.
   On the list of the initial eight claimants were 14 workers from
a Windham, Ohio, brick factory; a mother and two grown children
from the Johnstown, Pa., and Fort Montgomery, N.Y. areas; two Erie,
Pa., men who work at a General Electric plant; two couples and a
man from Morgantown, W.Va., where the three men work at West
Virginia University in the maintenance department; a woman from
Washington, Pa., who is a sales representative for an industrial
company; a five-member family from East Windsor, N.J.; a
74-year-old widow from Lebanon, Pa.; and a chiropractor and his
wife from New Brighton, Pa.
</TEXT>
