<FIRST>r i AM-Senegal-Mauritania     04-29 0376</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Senegal-Mauritania,0387</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senegalese Pillage Mauritanian Shops</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Note contents of 11th graf.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DAKAR, Senegal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senegalese ignored a state of emergency
Saturday and pillaged the few Mauritanian shops not damaged in
earlier violence that left at least 20 Mauritanians dead.
   Senegal was expected to begin airlifting about 20,000
Mauritanian refugees this weekend to their neighboring homeland
following the deadly rampage Friday.
   Police used tear gas to disperse crowds after declaring a state
of emergency Friday night and imposing a 10 p.m. to 6 a.m. curfew,
which brought relative calm to the capital overnight.
   But bands of Senegalese moved through the center of Dakar on
Saturday afternoon looking for Mauritanian-owned shops that were
not already damaged.
   The state of emergency, to be in effect for at least six days,
followed a rampage by Senegalese seeking out Mauritanians for
revenge attacks after the reported killing of an estimated 200
Senegalese in neighboring Mauritania last week.
   Press reports Saturday said at least 35 Mauritanians were killed
in the violence Friday in Dakar. Officials said Friday at least 20
people were killed.
   Police have been rounding up Mauritanians and giving them refuge
in a fairground outside Dakar. An estimated 20,000 Mauritanians had
been brought there by Saturday, according to Agence France-Presse,
the French news agency.
   France, the former colonial ruler of Senegal, announced Saturday
in Paris that it was furnishing five planes to airlift the
Mauritanians to their home and return to Dakar Senegalese hiding
out in the Mauritanian capital of Nouakchott.
   Spain on Saturday dispatched an air force transport jet loaded
with medicine, blankets and tents to Senegal and Mauritania.
   The violence began in a dispute April 9 between Mauritanian
shepherds and Senegalese peasants over grazing land at the border
of the two countries. Two Senegalese were killed in the incident.
   A week of scattered violence in Dakar erupted into a killing
rampage Monday and Tuesday in Nouakchott, in which as many as 200
people were reported killed. According to reports, most of the
corpses brought home had been decapitated, while some of the
injured returned to Dakar reportedly had their sex organs or limbs
mutilated.
   Word of the nature of the injuries and deaths spread through
Dakar, enraging the crowds who on Friday hunted down Mauritanians.
</TEXT>
