<FIRST>r i AM-Brazil-Strike     04-29 0340</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brazil-Strike,0350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brazilian Dockworkers End Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of dockworkers in seven
states in Brazil went back to work Saturday, ending a three-day
strike for higher pay, union officials said.
   Luis Carlos Silva Soares, a union official at Rio's port, said,
``All workers have returned to their jobs and the port slowly began
to resume normal operation today as of 7 a.m.''
   He said the Rio workers received pay increases of 50 percent.
They had been seeking 180 percent increases and a standardized pay
scale at all of the country's ports.
   The Union of Sea Navigation Agencies in Santos, which
coordinates and administers work by longshoremen, said the average
salary for a dockworker was about $600 per month.
   Inflation has been running at more than 1,000 percent a year.
The government froze most salaries in January but has allowed some
price increases.
   Silva Soares said dockworkers in the states of Rio Grande do
Sul, Santa Catarina, Parana, Espiritu Santo, Bahia and Pernambuco
also returned to work Saturday morning and were ``starting to
unload certain cargo, such as wheat shipments.''
   More than a third of 9,000 striking longshoreman in Santos, near
the industrial city of Sao Paulo and Brazil's busiest port, ended
their strike that began April 10, according to Jairo de Galvao, a
union leader in Santos.
   But he said much of the port, which normally handles 72,000 tons
of cargo per day and 35 percent of Brazil's exports, remained idle.
   ``About 5,500 mechanics, unloaders and inspectors are still to
vote on the offer and probably won't return to work until Monday,''
he said.
   The Sao Paulo State Dock Company was reporting losses of $1
million per day in uncollected loading and unloading fees.
   Company officials said 39 ships were docked in Santos waiting to
be unloaded and another 42 were anchored outside the port waiting
to enter.
   The strike did not affect oil shipments. The state oil monopoly
Petrobras has its own loading terminals and workers whose union did
not join the strike.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
