<FIRST>r i AM-Nicaragua-CostaRica     04-29 0365</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nicaragua-Costa Rica,0376</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nicaragua Investigating Activities of Costa Rican Envoy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RODOLFO GARCIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Foreign Ministry is investigating
reports that Costa Rica's ambassador participated in plans to
discredit the Sandinista government, the Sandinistas' newspaper
reported Saturday.
   The Barricada newspaper quoted Deputy Foreign Minister Jose Leon
Talavera as saying the ministry ``is evaluating with extreme
caution'' information that Costa Rican Ambassador Farid Ayales
engaged in activities ``outside his diplomatic functions.''
   The pro-government newspaper El Nuevo Diario reported Friday
that Ayales had met with Nicaraguan opposition leaders and a U.S.
Embassy official ``to prepare a foreign campaign of accusations''
against the leftist government.
   El Nuevo Diario said the campaign would seek to discredit
electoral law changes approved April 18 by the legislature for the
general election next February.
   The newspaper attributed its information to opposition party
sources, whom it did not name. It did not identify the U.S. Embassy
official allegedly involved.
   Nicaragua's opposition parties have denounced the new electoral
rules, saying they give the Sandinista party control over the
Supreme Elections Council that will supervise the balloting.
   Talavera told Barricada there are no restrictions on foreign
diplomats meeting with opposition figures but it was ``intolerable
under international laws'' for diplomats to ``become activists or
directors of local political organizations.''
   Talaveres also said Nicaraguan officials had ``made some
observations'' to Ayales several months ago about his conduct in
Nicaragua.
   Costa Rican officials have declined to comment on the El Nuevo
Diario report.
   Also Saturday, a Costa Rican newspaper reported that a
Nicaraguan air force flight engineer had defected to Costa Rica and
asked authorities for political asylum.
   The San Jose newspaper La Republica identified the flight
engineer as Jesus Ferrey Alvarado, 40, and said he sailed a small
boat to Costa Rica's Playa Rajada and asked for asylum. It said
Ferrey Alvarado is a specialist in Soviet-built MI-17 troop
transport helicopters.
   Costa Rican civil guard and immigration authorities could not be
reached for comment.
   On April 21 Sandinista air force Capt. Reinaldo Aranda Guido
defected to Costa Rica, piloting a small plane owned by a freight
company from Nicaragua's Corn Island to Puerto Limon on Costa
Rica's Atlantic coast.
