<FIRST>r i AM-Iran-Germany     04-29 0381</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-Germany,0390</SECOND>
<BYLINE>Iranian Newspaper Calls For Expulsion of West German Diplomats
^By HASAN MROUE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Iranian newspaper on Saturday called
for the explusion of West German diplomats from Tehran, calling
them ``spies disguised as diplomats'' and part of an American
espionage network.
   The official Islamic Republic News Agency carried excerpts from
the editorial in the daily Kayhan, which said the ouster of German
diplomats was the best response to ``the mischief of the Bonn
government.''
   Spokesmen for the West German Foreign Ministry in Bonn were not
immediately available for comment Saturday night.
   Iranian Prime Minister Hussein Musavi claimed Tuesday that some
agents of an alleged U.S. spy network in Iran were communicating
with the Americans through West German embassies in Europe.
   In addition, Information Minister Mohammad Mohammadi-Rayshahri
said Wednesday the agents all were linked to the CIA base at
Weisbaden, near Frankfurt in West Germany.
   The widely read Kayhan said Rayshahri's information was based on
intelligence reports and confessions by those arrested. Iran did
not say how many people had been rounded up in connection with the
affair.
   The liberal daily said the news of German involvement was
sufficient cause to sever relations with West Germany, said IRNA.
   The agency, monitored in Nicosia, quoted Kayhan as describing
the West German capital as being a haven for Iranian opposition
members, who use it to launch ``hostile operations against Iranian
interests.''
   The newspaper's call comes five days after the Iranian Foreign
Ministry threatened to reduce trade relations with West Germany,
accusing it of helping archenemy Iraq manufacture missiles and
internationally banned chemical weapons.
   West Germany is one of 14 countries that recalled their envoys
from Tehran in February to protest the death threat against British
novelist Salman Rushdie by Iranian leader Ayatollah Ruhollah
Khomeini. Khomeini said Rushdie blasphemed Islam in his novel,
``The Satanic Verses.''
   Kayhan said West Germany always takes similar stands to those
taken by the United States when it comes to ``adopting a position
with respect to Iran ... this year the German government took sides
with Salman Rushdie.''
   Kayhan also accused the Bonn government of being ``insincere''
in its friendship, despite Iran's goodwill shown in the release of
two West German hostages who were held with pro-Iranian Shiite
extemists in Lebanon.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890429-0104 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-29-89 1824EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-DinosaurExtinction     04-29 0663</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dinosaur Extinction,0683</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shower of Meteorites Killed Off Dinosaurs, Scientist Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KAREN SCHWARTZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A huge asteroid skipping off Earth at a
low angle may have kicked thousands of giant boulders into orbit,
creating a shower of meteorites that gradually killed off the
dinosaurs, a scientist says.
   Brown University geologist Peter Schultz's research seeks to
answer a key objection to the theory that dinosaurs and many other
species 66 million years ago died out because a large object struck
the planet, raising a dust cloud that blocked sunlight and wiped
out food sources.
   Fossil experts have pointed out that the dinosaurs died over
hundreds of thousands of years, not all at once.
   Advocates of the theory responded by suggesting that a series of
asteroids, comets or meteorites hit the planet. The new theory by
Schultz and colleague Donald Gault of the Murphys Center of
Planetology in Murphys, Calif., explains how that might have
happened.
   In experiments using BB pellets and dry ice, the pair observed
that a projectile hitting a surface at an angle breaks into as many
as a dozen major pieces and thousands of smaller ones, which then
continue along the same trajectory at roughly half the original
velocity.
   Schultz suggests an object hit Earth, then ``literally skipped
off the surface'' and fragmented. ``They would continue to go
perhaps halfway around the Earth, (causing) thousands of other
devastating impacts,'' he said in an interview last week.
   An oblique impact would also kick up a tremendous amount of
debris. ``We found from doing these experiments that we produced an
incredible vapor cloud,'' Schultz said.
   The scientists tested their theory by firing BBs into pits of
dry ice to test sand trajectory paths and vapor formation.
   They concluded that a meteor striking the Earth at an angle
would spew out debris with enough speed to place it in orbit,
allowing it to remain in space long enough to cause large-scale
destruction, Schultz said.
   He said that within 100 years the cloud of debris would collapse
into a Saturn-like ring which would put part of the Earth in
darkness.
   ``The ring would last anywhere from 100,000 years to 10 million
years,'' said Schultz.
   Schultz, who presented his theory in March at the annual
international Lunar Planetary Science Conference in Houston, has
submitted it for publication. He plans to use his research to
examine the effects of the impact on Earth's climate.
   William Clemens, a professor of paleontology at the University
of California at Berkeley, said he still believes the mass
extinction was caused by a climatic change, rather than a collision.
   ``I would argue against any hypothesis that calls for long
periods of darkness and great cooling,'' he said. Some animals
survived through the period and he said that can be explained only
by a decrease in temperature of no more than 1 degree or 2. Other
scientists support alternate extinction theories, including
volcanic destruction.
   But Schultz said his theory is ``the link'' to the impact theory
first proposed by Luis and Walter Alvarez in 1980.
   Under Schultz's theory, as the ring decayed, debris would again
pummel the Earth. ``Every day we have a meteor shower,'' he said.
   He said the theory addresses the evidence of an extended
extinction; non-uniform dispersal of meteoritic matter; the absence
of a crater of sufficient size for a single devastating impact and
evidence of massive, intensive fires.
   ``Schultz and Gault are world-class experts on impact mechanics
and anything they come up with will certainly be looked at with
respect and interest by others involved in the work,'' said Walter
Alvarez. He declined to comment on the theory in detail.
   Schultz, an associate professor of planetary geology, said
studies of impacts on other planets suggest collisions generally
occur at angles.
   Angular collisions leave craters with very distinctive shapes.
``We can compare the rate at which oblique impacts occur on the
moon with what we expect theoretically and it fits,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
