<FIRST>r i AM-Paraguay-Elections     04-29 0387</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Paraguay-Elections,0403</SECOND>
<HEAD>Paraguayan Campaign Closes In Spirit Of Fraternity</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED McCULLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Provisional President Andres Rodriguez
and his rivals joined hands with thousands of other Paraguayans
Saturday in a show of solidarity at the end of a campaign for
elections to restore democracy.
   ``After long years of falseness, the Paraguayan people will
elect for the first time, freely and responsibly, those who in
their names will administer and promote the common good,'' said the
Rev. Ismael Rolon, the capital's Roman Catholic Archbishop.
   Elections are set for Monday to choose a government to replace
the deposed regime of President Gen. Alfredo Stroessner, who was
toppled Feb. 3 in a coup led by Rodriguez. The coup ended a
dictatorship in power since 1954.
   Voters will elect a president, 36 senators, and 72 national
deputies.
   As the throng of several thousand people left the national
cathedral in downtown Asuncion for a walk through the city
Saturday, marchers also reached out to traffic police and held
their hands aloft.
   ``We're here to reflect and pray that God helps us construct
democracy in Paraguay,'' said 19-year-old Shirley Villalba, a
medical student.
   U.S. Ambassador Timothy Towell stood at the rear of the crowd.
He watched as political rivals, former exiles, government
officials, and Paraguayans rich and poor held hands in what they
called a ``chain of hope.''
   ``This has never happened before,'' Towell said. ``That song
(Beloved Country) was banned under Stroessner. Now the government
candidate sings it and the people hold hands with the police.''
   Independent polls indicate Rodriguez, who is running for the
governing Colorado Party, will win up to 70 percent of the vote.
The surveys say Domingo Laino, presidential candidate of the
Authentic Radical Liberal Party, will gain 17 percent, with six
other candidates trailing far behind.
   The Colorado slate of legislative candidates is projected to
tally about 60 percent of the vote and thus gain an automatic
two-thirds control of congress.
   The party has controlled the government since 1947.
   Since taking power, Rodriguez has lifted restrictions on
political parties, restored civil liberties, accused former
government officials of corruption and torture, and allowed exiles
to return. Laino says, however, that farmers are still clamoring
for land, workers want enforcement of labor laws, politicians
expect constitutional reform, and women demand equal rights.
</TEXT>
