<HEAD>Georgians Attacking Families Of Troops, General Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 12th graf, `Azruyan said...,' with 1 graf to restore dropped
first reference to Azruyan. Pick up 13th pvs, `In Azerbaijan...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Residents in the Soviet republic of Georgia have
beaten family members of army soldiers because they unfairly blame
the troops for bloody clashes with pro-independence demonstrators,
an army general said Saturday.
   At least 20 people died in the unrest earlier this month in
Tbilisi, the Georgian capital. Georgians say the troops attacked a
peaceful demonstration with shovels, clubs and harmful gases.
   Gen. I.N. Rodionov, commander of the Caucasus military district,
said Tbilisi residents are blaming Red Army soldiers for the clash,
and he strongly implied that troops of the Interior Ministry were
to blame.
   Rodionov, speaking on the evening news show Vremya, said wives
and children of Red Army soldiers have been beaten and their
apartments stoned in retaliation for the crackdown. He gave no
other details.
   He said Interior Ministry troops should have handled the
demonstration without the aid of Red Army soldiers and suggested
that ministry troops wear special uniforms so they can be
distinguished from the Red Army.
   He said the ministry troops also used the harmful gas that
dissidents claimed was nerve gas.
   The Georgian health minister said last week that troops used an
unidentified chemical that caused at least two of the deaths and
several serious injuries.
   Rodionov, like other Soviet officials, maintained the substance
used against demonstrators was tear gas. He also said he personally
opposed the use of troops to crush the demonstrations.
   Meanwhile, in other parts of the Caucasus region, plans for May
Day celebrations were canceled in Soviet Armenia for fear they
could turn into pro-independence demonstrations.
   The military commander of Yerevan, the Armenian capital, issued
a call for calm Saturday, asking residents not to allow themselves
to be incited into a confrontation with authorities, said Rafael
Popoyan, a newsman for the official radio station in Yerevan.
   Yerevan has been under curfew for more than six months to curb
ethnic conflicts that killed more than 90 people in Armenia and
neighboring Azerbaijan in 1988. Armenians are seeking to be
reunited with Nagorno-Karabakh, an ethnic Armenian region of
Azerbaijan.
   Leon Azruyan, of the official radio station in Yerevan, said
officials also cited the grim feelings left by the Armenian
earthquake for the cancellation of a May Day parade. An estimated
25,000 died in the December quake.
   In Azerbaijan, the official news agency Azerinform denied rumors
of new violence in the enclave of Nakhichevan, which borders
Armenia. Azerinform said the rumors were spread by people upset
about a border dispute over an orchard that surveyors determined
belongs to Armenia rather than Azerbaijan.
   The dispatch indicated that passions rose in the village of
Tsadarak, which lost the orchard, but there were no deaths or
injuries.
</TEXT>
