<FIRST>u i AM-Israel 2ndLd-Writethru a0536 04-29 0750</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0536,0768</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reports: 20 Wounded In Territories, Boy Wounded By Settlers Dies</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 15 grafs to UPDATE with more wounded, Jewish settler
detained in shooting of Arab. Pick up 14th pvs, `Arens, speaking...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli soldiers shot and wounded at least 18
Palestinians Saturday in the occupied Gaza Strip, Arab hospital
officials said, and a 14-year-old boy who Arabs said was shot by
Jewish settlers died, according to Israeli and Arab reports.
   The Israeli military command said a report from Gaza listed only
three wounded. It reported another two wounded in stone-throwing
clashes in the West Bank towns of Jenin and Tulkarem.
   Also Saturday, Foreign Minister Moshe Arens accused the PLO of
``trying to impose a rule of terror'' to sabotage an Israeli
proposal for elections in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   In the West Bank town of El Bireh, Palestinian assailants tried
to set fire to the house of the Israeli-appointed Arab mayor,
Hassan Tawil, and slightly damaged a door, the army command said.
   The PLO-linked underground leaders of the uprising have called
for the resignation of Israeli-appointed mayors. It was the second
attack on Tawil. On June 7, 1988, he was stabbed in the chest.
   In the West Bank town of Jericho, attackers firebombed and
burned a restaurant belonging to a Palestinian suspected of being a
pro-Israeli collaborator, the national news agency Itim said.
   Palestinians in the Gaza Strip defied an army curfew and
protested casualties in the seaside strip, home to 650,000
Palestinians.
   Merchants in Gaza shut their stores in a commercial strike to
commemorate the ``martyrs,'' or Palestinians killed by army
gunfire, Arab reports said.
   An Arab reporter in Gaza City said youths erected roadblocks,
burned tires and hung at least 20 Palestinian flags from electric
wires. The army clamped a curfew on several neighborhoods in the
city and on three refugee camps in the Gaza Strip, forcing 80,000
residents to stay inside their homes.
   But the curfew failed to prevent sporadic stone-throwing
clashes. In Gaza City's Sabra neighborhood, 100 people rushed to
the street, ``shouting the names of martyrs until the army
dispersed them with tear gas,'' a witness said.
   Hospital officials said they treated at least 18 Palestinians
who were wounded by troops during clashes in seven Gaza areas,
including a 9-year-old boy from the Jabaliya refugee camp who was
shot in the leg.
   At Jerusalem's Hadassah Hospital, 14-year-old Nader Naim Dana
died of two gunshot wounds to the head suffered Friday during a
clash in the West Bank town of Hebron, Israel radio and Arab
reports said.
   Arab reports from Hebron said at the time that the boy was shot
by Jewish settlers. The army said it was investigating the shooting.
   Itim said police detained a 52-year-old Jewish settler for
questioning Saturday night on suspicion of involvement in the
shooting.
   It said the settler, a resident of Kiryat Arba near Hebron,
allegedly opened fire with his Uzi submachine gun after Palestinian
youths stoned his car in Hebron. His name was not given.
   Arens, speaking on Israel radio, said Palestinians themselves
were to blame for casualties among children and teen-agers.
   ``You have here not only a clash between two peoples ... but
also a clash between two civilizations. Facing us you find people
who have been raised with a tradition of fanaticism, brutality, of
lack of regard for human life _ I'd say lack of regard for their
own life,'' Arens said.
   Arens accused the Palestine Liberation Organization of trying to
sabotage an Israeli proposal for elections in the West Bank and the
Gaza Strip by attacking Palestinians suspected of collaborating
with Israeli authorities.
   At least 40 suspected collaborators have been killed since the
December 1987 start of the anti-Israeli uprising. The rebellion has
claimed the lives of 456 Palestinians and 18 Israelis.
   ``People are being hacked to death by axes ....'' Arens said.
``A woman in Nablus was raped for three days, and after that her
arms were broken. People are burned alive, people are knifed,
people are being shot and the PLO is trying to impose a rule of
terror.''
   The election idea, put forward by Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir
during a visit to Washington this month, suggests negotiations with
elected Palestinian representatives on a period of limited
self-rule for the territories.
   Palestinian leaders in the occupied lands and the PLO reject the
proposal, saying elections can only be held after Israeli withdraws
from the territories.
