<FIRST>r i AM-Poland     04-29 0325</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland,0338</SECOND>
<HEAD>Walesa Opens Opposition Campaign for June Election</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GDANSK, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Solidarity leader Lech Walesa on Saturday
opened the opposition's campaign for June 4 elections at a rally
outside the Lenin Shipyard attended by more than 200 candidates.
   ``In our country something must change and you must be the
ones'' to make those changes, Walesa told the candidates at the
rally in Gdansk, the birthplace of his newly-legalized labor
movement.
   He noted there is only five weeks before the election and urged
the candidates to begin campaigning immediately.
   The elections will the the first in Poland with opposition
candidates participating since 1947. Runoff elections are set for
June 18.
   A political bargain reached with the ruling Communist Party on
April 5 again legalized Solidarity and allowed the opposition to
run for 161 seats in the 460-member Sejm, or parliament.
   The agreement also creates a new 100-member Senate with
opposition candidates permitted to run for all the seats.
   Almost all of the 261 opposition candidates traveled to Gdansk
for the opening rally at the Lenin Shipyard. The shipyard became
the birthplace of Solidarity during nationwide strikes in the fall
of 1980.
   Solidarity was suspended in December 1981 and subsequently
outlawed by parliament.
   On the train carrying many of the candidates on the 3{-hour
journey from Warsaw to the port city of Gdansk, candidates and
their advisers huddled in the compartments and exchanged notes with
other groups.
   In one compartment, Adam Michnik, a historian and candidate for
the Sejm from Katowice, laughed at an article in the Communist
Party newspaper Trybuna Ludu that characterized him as an
``extemist element'' in the opposition.
   ``They are making my campaign for me,'' he said.
   The candidates were approved last week at a meeting in Warsaw by
the Solidarity-led national Citizens Committee, which is
coordinating the campaign.
   Communist Party candidates are to be announced after a party
conference Thursday and Friday.
</TEXT>
