<FIRST>r a AM-SovietDefectors     04-29 0601</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet Defectors,0621</SECOND>
<HEAD>Defectors Tell Of Planning, Deception</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two young Soviets seeking political
asylum in the United States say they began scheming two years ago
to defect, and forged documents that enabled them to travel to
Little Diomede Island in the Bering Strait last weekend.
   ``It was not possible to make it in a legal way,'' said Anatoly
Tkachenko, a 24-year-old journalist from Moscow.
   ``We are very sorry that we kind of marred and soured the
ceremony at Little Diomede, but there was no other way,'' Tkachenko
added.
   Tkachenko and Alexander Genkin, also 24 and from Moscow,
defected last Sunday while they were on Little Diomede for the
signing of a protocol designed to ease travel restrictions between
Alaska and Siberia.
   Both men worked for a monthly Moscow newspaper that serves the
government's international affairs ministry and the Moscow state
college for international affairs.
   When they learned a Soviet delegation would be traveling to
Little Diomede for the signing ceremony, they forged papers
authorizing them to cover the event for the newspaper, Tkachenko
said at a news conference Friday.
   The pair typed an application, obtained a special stamp to
verify it had been authorized, and took it to the headquarters of
the Bering Bridge Expedition.
   The expedition is a team of Soviet and American adventurers
skiing and dog-sledding its way along the Siberian and Alaskan
coasts. The signing ceremony coincided with their arrival at the
international dateline in the Bering Strait between Little Diomede
Island and the Soviet island of Big Diomede about three miles away.
   ``We were very anxious and apprehensive about our even taking
part in this delegation'' because of the forged permission,
Tkachenko said. If the two had been found out, ``I think we would
have been in prison for three or four years,'' he said.
   Both men called in sick to explain their absence while traveling
to Alaska, he said.
   Tkachenko, who speaks English fluently, did most of the talking
at the news conference and translated for Genkin, who speaks very
little English.
   Tkachenko said he doubts the defections will affect U.S.-Soviet
relations or hamper efforts to open the Alaska-Siberia border.
   He said neither man told relatives or anyone else about the plan
to defect, and said he didn't think Soviet authorities would
retaliate against their parents.
   Tkachenko said both men would like to continue working as
journaists if their requests for asylum are approved.
   ``I am very interested in this field, especially in American TV
journalism,'' Tkachenko said. ``It was my idea for a very long time
to be somehow involved in this field, you know. Maybe I can get a
job at any company or channel as an expert in Soviet affairs
because I studied international affairs.''
   He said Genkin wants to work in print journalism once he learns
English.
   Tkachenko said the absence of censorship in the United States
was a bigger attraction than money.
   ``There is still a one-party system of censorhip and an
unequivocal belief in Lenin's ideas, even with Gorbachev,'' he said.
   ``I think if you are a journalist and you wish to work in
freedom ... to be creative in your job, that's the most important
thing for you,'' Tkachenko said. ``Not just the money or the
possibility to live in a big house. It's not the main thing for me,
and I think for Alexander too.''
   Tkachenko said he ultimately wants to live in New York or
Washington.
   Gary Johnson, regional director of the Immigration and
Naturalization Service, said it will be several weeks before a
decision is made on their requests for asylum.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
