<SECOND>AM-Hamrick Honored,0341</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Twiggs County's Matt Dillon' Honored For 48 Years Wearing A Shield</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JEFFERSONVILLE, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Earl Hamrick, the law in Twiggs
County for 48 years, was compared Saturday with Marshal Matt Dillon
of ``Gunsmoke'' in a ceremony honoring him as the nation's
longest-serving sheriff.
   A marble marker was unveiled on the courthouse lawn as part of
the tribute to Hamrick in this central Georgia town of about 9,300
people. The marker features a bas relief of Hamrick's face and a
brief history of his career.
   Hamrick, who retired Dec. 31 and is believed to be 86 years old,
thanked the people of Twiggs County for electing him over the years.
   ``I also want to thank every law enforcement agency in Georgia
and in the United States,'' he said. ``I worked with all of them,
and I had the best relationship with everybody.
   ``I go to conventions and Yankees ask me how come I keep getting
elected,'' he said. ``I tell them, `Just being a dang good sheriff
is all I know!'''
   U.S. District Judge Duross Fitzpatrick had high praise for
Hamrick.
   ``He was capable of doing the job, he liked to do the job, he
had good humor and he was utterly fearless,'' Fitzpatrick said.
   ``Earl represents the best of politics in America,'' Fitzpatrick
said, adding that Hamrick's retirement was like Dodge City's Dillon
riding off into the sunset.
   Upson County Sheriff Merrill Greathouse, an official with the
National Sheriff's Association, said he couldn't find another
sheriff who had served 48 years. He said the next highest was a
sheriff who served 36 years.
   Hamrick was appointed sheriff emeritus for the state of Georgia
by Gov. Joe Frank Harris.
   Former U.S. Sen. Herman Talmadge, D-Ga., a longtime friend of
the Hamrick family, said that during Hamrick's 48 years of service
there was not one murder that went unsolved.
   ``I doubt there's another sheriff in the country who can say
that,'' Talmadge said.
