<SECOND>AM-Obit-Nord,0263</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Beat King,' hungry i Founder Dies</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: hungry i is cq lowercase.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eric ``Big Daddy'' Nord, known as the
``king of the beat generation'' and whose hungry i nightspot in San
Francisco showcased Lenny Bruce and Mort Sahl, has died after
several years of failing health. He was 69.
   ``Nord was a poet and a philosopher who constantly sought an
audience willing to hear his message,'' said Telemachos A. Greanias
of Los Gatos, a friend who wrote a tribute to Nord after his death
Wednesday at the Skyline Convalescent Home.
   ``His words were angry, but his tone and meaning were reform in
the interest of humanity.''
   Born Harry Pastor to a German industrialist and his American
wife, Nord's family came to California and he quickly became
involved in the beat culture.
   In 1950, Nord opened the hungry i, a music and comedy club that
featured rebellious satirists like Bruce and Sahl. He later left
San Francisco, blaming his move on cigarette smoke at the
nightclub, drugs and misguided beat generation leaders.
   After an abortive attempt to set up a vegetarian commune in
Guatemala, Nord opened a string of coffee houses in California.
   Dubbed ``Big Daddy'' because of his 6-foot-8, 400-pound frame,
Nord spent his later years in Los Gatos, just south of San Jose.
His death followed several years of illness related to his weight
as well as heart and kidney disease, Greanias said.
   Nord is survived by three children, three brothers, six
grandchildren and a nephew.
</TEXT>
