<FIRST>r a AM-Obit-Deskey     04-29 0221</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Deskey,0228</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prolific Interior And Packaging Designer Dies At 94</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VERO BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Donald Deskey, an innovative industrial
designer whose credits range from the interiors of New York's Radio
City Music Hall to packaging for a variety of household products,
died Saturday. He was 94.
   Deskey died of pneumonia at Indian River Memorial Hospital, said
Barbara Smith, a night supervisor at the hospital.
   ``Donald Deskey was among the leading figures to introduce
modern design in the United States in the late 1920s,'' said David
A. Hanks, who with Jennifer Tober wrote ``Donald Deskey: Decorative
Designs and Interiors.''
   Deskey, whose career spanned more than half a century, was
associated with the Procter and Gamble Co. for 20 years. His
package design for the company's Crest toothpaste has not changed
since its introduction in the 1950s.
   An adept interior designer as well, he created apartments for
such prominent clients as Adam Gimbel in 1927, Abby Aldrich
Rockefeller in 1929 and Helena Rubinstein in 1930.
   His 1932 design for the interiors of Radio City are widely
hailed as an Art Deco masterpiece.
   Born in Blue Earth, Minn., Deskey had homes in Scotland, Jamaica
and Florida as well as an apartment in Manhattan. He retired to
Vero Beach in 1975.
   He is survived by his wife, Katherine, two sons and two
grandchildren.
</TEXT>
