<FIRST>r a AM-SpillBills     04-29 0323</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Spill Bills,0331</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Passes Package of Oil-Spill Legislation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN S. AKRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JUNEAU, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A package of bills aimed at protecting
Alaska from another devastating oil spill like the one that fouled
Prince William Sound was passed by the state Senate with little
trouble Saturday.
   Reacting to the largest oil spill in the nation's history, the
Republican-led Senate acted with unusual speed to move the six
bills through the chamber and to the House.
   However, it appeared unlikely that the Democrat-controlled House
would approve the entire package before adjournment, which is
scheduled for May 9.
   The Senate action came five weeks after the tanker Exxon Valdez
struck a reef, spewing more than 10 million gallons of crude oil
into the fish- and wildlife-rich sound.
   The Senate bills would increase civil fines for spill damage;
impose a surcharge on oil producers to boost the state's
spill-response fund; prevent oil companies from deducting spill
costs from their oil-production taxes; require the state to create
spill contingency plans; establish a spill-response office and
cleanup corps; and create a commission to investigate the Exxon
Valdez spill.
   More than a dozen other spill-related bills are still pending in
both chambers. House Speaker Sam Cotten, a Democrat, said House
members have been studying the bills and will decide early this
week which ones will get top priority.
   ``It isn't like we've been waiting around to see what the Senate
did,'' he said.
   Sen. John Binkley, a Republican, voted against all the bills
passed Saturday, except for the investigation commission measure.
``I think that we're acting too hastily on these issues,'' he said.
   Gov. Steve Cowper said Friday that he, too, favors a slower
approach to oil-spill legislation.
   ``I don't think that we need major legislation in this session,
aside from the funding mechanisms and aside from the body that will
be investigating this incident on the part of the state,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
