<HEAD>Tawana Brawley Says Report Not True</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note contents 4th graf.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tawana Brawley on Saturday denied a newspaper
report that her claims of abduction and rape by a gang of white men
were a fabrication.
   The black teen-ager's claims made national headlines and her
family's advisers kept Miss Brawley and her mother from appearing
before a grand jury, claiming the state investigation was a coverup
to protect the rapists.
   But the grand jury concluded last year that Miss Brawley had
faked being raped.
   Miss Brawley was found Nov. 28, 1987, in a plastic garbage bag,
smeared with feces and with racial epithets scrawled on her body.
At the time, she was 15.
   Newsday reported Thursday that Miss Brawley had admitted to her
boyfriend that she and her mother made up the story to keep the
mother's lover from beating the teen-ager.
   But Miss Brawley told a news conference, ``My father has never
beaten me,'' referring to her mother's live-in boyfriend.
   ``I am not afraid of him,'' she said. ``I love him with all of
my heart.''
   The newspaper said Miss Brawley made the admission two weeks ago
to Daryl T. Rodriguez, 19, who became her boyfriend a few weeks
before the events of late November.
   Miss Brawley would not answer questions about the newspaper
report but said of Rodriguez, ``I was really shocked he would say
something like this.''

