<FIRST>u w AM-Bush-Correspondents     04-29 0439</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Correspondents,425</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Pokes Fun at Self at White House Correspondents' Dinner</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURIE ASSEO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush celebrated his 100th day in
office Saturday by bringing along comedian Garry Shandling to help
poke fun at himself at the White House Correspondents' Association
dinner.
   ``I'll tell you how nifty, how swell _ gosh, what fun it is to
be president,'' Bush joked in a speech to the reporters, editors
and their guests.
   Shandling said Bush had pulled him from a line at a White House
tour earlier in the day and asked him to perform at the dinner. ``I
thought he was joking because I'd really never taken him seriously
before,'' the comedian said.
   Bush promised the reporters some hard news: ``My first nominee
to the Supreme Court _ John Tower. What we need is a little
justice,'' he said, referring to the diminutive former Texas
senator who was rejected as secretary of defense.
   The president drew his biggest laugh by telling the audience he
was relieved that ``there won't be time tonight for my slide shows
of the trip to Honduras.'' Bush has refused recently to comment on
his trip to Honduras as vice president during a time when,
according to documents released during Oliver North's Iran-Contra
trial, the Reagan administration was seeking aid for the Nicaraguan
rebels from other countries at a time U.S. aid was outlawed by
Congress.
   The president said he was growing accustomed to being tagged
``Barbara's husband.''
   Noting some reporters have said his rigorous public schedule was
keeping them busier than former President Reagan did, Bush said,
``That's the first time that I have ever been accused of keeping
anybody awake.''
   And he joked that at least the incoming president of the
correspondents' group, Johanna Neuman of USA Today, ``can blame her
troubles on her predecessor.'' Some Bush aides were chastised
recently for comparing his work habits too favorably with Reagan's.
   Shandling said he had told Bush he was happy to appear, but ``I
hope you won't ask me to do that State of the Union thing.''
   Four White House correspondents were honored at the dinner.
Jeremiah O'Leary of the Washington Times and the outgoing president
of the group, was given the Merriman Smith Memorial Award for
reporting under deadline pressure.
   Owen Ullmann of Knight-Ridder received the Aldo Beckman Memorial
Award for journalistic excellence.
   Christopher Drew of the Chicago Tribune received the Edgar Allan
Poe Award for fairness and objectivity in reporting on subjects of
national or regional importance. Jim Angle of National Public
Radio, treasurer of the correspondents' group, was given honorable
mention for the award.
</TEXT>
