<FIRST>r a AM-ForestFire     04-29 0231</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Forest Fire,0238</SECOND>
<HEAD>80-Foot Flames Force Firefighters Back In Osceola Forest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OSCEOLA NATIONAL FOREST, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Firefighters retreated from
a wall of flames about 80 feet high Saturday as they battled a
forest fire that has charred 10,500 acres, forestry officials said.
   ``There are times that the flames are so high that they are
pulling back and can't work the fire directly because it's so
dangerous,'' said Cheryl Summers, spokeswoman for the Florida
Division of Forestry in Tallahassee.
   The fire was headed east but switched Saturday to a northernly
direction, forcing the 165 firefighters to redraw their battle
lines, said Bill Scaramellino, forestry spokesman.
   ``The fire more or less blew up,'' Scaramellino said.
   The wall of 80-foot flames was a half mile long and within a
half mile of State Road 2, which is two miles south of the
Florida-Georgia border.
   Firefighters were trying to control the fire by dropping water
on it from aircraft. The strategy wasn't very effective because the
flames were so high, Ms. Summers said.
   Firefighters from Georgia and Arkansas have joined the battle.
   The fire, reported Wednesday, apparently started when the
transmisson in a logging vehicle broke down and sent off sparks
that started the fire in land adjacent to the Osceola National
Forest, Ms. Summers said.
   No structures have been threatened by the fire and no one has
been seriously hurt, Scaramellino said.
</TEXT>
