<FIRST>u i AM-Mexico-US 3dLd-Writethru a0576 04-29 0560</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico-US, 3d Ld-Writethru, a0576,0578</SECOND>
<HEAD>Debt, Drugs and Democracy Mark U.S.-Mexico Talks</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 4 grafs after 3rd pvs, `It is...' to UPDATE with final
communique. Pick up 4th pvs, `On Friday...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>IXTAPA, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. senators on Saturday encouraged
Mexico to continue efforts to combat drug trafficking and modernize
the economy during bilateral talks on debt, drugs and democracy.
   Sen. Christopher J. Dodd, D-Conn., praised President Carlos
Salinas de Gortari's anti-drug campaign. In return, he said, the
United States would support Mexico's efforts to cut payments on its
$107.4 billion foreign debt.
   ``It is a seamless garment when you start talking about
confidence in a government,'' Dodd said in an interview.
   The delegations issued a communique after the two-day meeting of
U.S. and Mexican lawmakers ended Saturday night.
   They said they were prepared to ``promote the establishment of a
Mexico-U.S. intergovernmental consultive commission for the control
of narcotic and psychotropic substance abuse.''
   The sides also ``urged their respective governments to support
an international drug summit of the presidents of the Western
Hemisphere.''
   Mexico's delegation called for urgent measures to help Mexico
cut its debt payments and the U.S. group suggested Mexico broaden
the alternatives it is presenting to bankers in debt negotiations.
   On Friday, the opening day of the 28th annual meeting, Dodd read
a letter to Salinas signed by 68 U.S. senators praising the Mexican
president for his commitment to fight drug trafficking.
   The U.S. Senate votes in May over whether Mexico is adequately
fighting the illicit narcotics trade. Both Dodd and Sen. Phil
Gramm, R-Texas, said they expected a positive vote.
   Dodd said many U.S. lawmakers were impressed with Salinas'
efforts to streamline the Mexican economy and liberalize its
foreign trade.
   ``He is moving at a pace that's impressive. There is this very
strong feeling about his government,'' Dodd said.
   Gramm was more skeptical.
   ``I want to be shown. I've heard all the good words before,'' he
said in an interview.
   But Gramm added he would give Salinas ``the benefit of the
doubt.''
   Mexico is negotiating with foreign creditor banks to slice its
annual debt servicing bill by at least $7 billion. The country paid
$9 billion in interest and $5 billion in principal in 1988 and
servicing will reach an anticipated $16 billion this year.
   At this Pacific seaside resort, the American delegation
encountered Mexican lawmakers representing opposition parties,
which are amply represented in Mexico's Congress for the first time.
   Opposition delegates buttonholed their U.S. counterparts to
lodge complaints that democracy has yet to develop south of the
border.
   ``We have to start a genuine dialogue among real
parliamentarians, among people speaking for the people, '' said
Porfirio Munoz Ledo, a leftist opposition senator.
   Salinas, the keynote speaker Friday, took note of the new
opposition presence in Mexican politics. Nearly a third of Mexico's
36-person delegation came from opposition parties.
   But Teresa Otono Gurca, a federal deputy from the conservative
National Action Party, or PAN, said the U.S. delegation was more
interested in encouraging Salinas, especially on waging the war
against drugs, than in listening to opposition challenges to the
legitimacy of Salinas' election last July.
   ``They think that without the ruling Institutional Revolutionary
Party, there is no stability in Mexico,'' Otono said of the
American lawmakers.
   Delegates from both countries characterized the meeting as open
and frank.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
