<NOTE>By The Associated Press</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   On the first observance of Workers Memorial Day, the
government's record on worker safety was criticized, a bugler
played ``Taps,'' and roll calls were read of the hundreds of people
who died on the job in the United States last year.
   From northern Maine to southern California and Honolulu, workers
paused Friday to remember those killed in job-related accidents.
The events were organized by labor unions to highlight workplace
safety.
   The unions chose Friday because it is the 19th anniversary of
the founding of the Occupational Safety and Health Administration.
   An estimated 10,000 people are killed each year on the job. The
jobs that carry the highest risk of fatal injury, according to the
government, are in mining, transportation, construction and
agriculture.
