<FIRST>a e AM-APArts:BaseballAuthor Adv04   04-29 0703</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AP Arts: Baseball Author, Adv 04,0722</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv 04</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Thurs AMs, May 4 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Professor Turns To Baseball For First Novel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN J. MULLINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Growing up in New Jersey and dreaming of playing
major league baseball, Bill Littlefield hoped Willie Mays would
move next door and teach him all he needed to know.
   ``Then when he retired, I'd just move in,'' he said.
   But Mays and the New York Giants moved to San Francisco, and
Littlefield became a college professor and radio commentator.
   That didn't end his love of baseball, as is clear in his first
novel, ``Prospect,'' which was published by Houghton Mifflin Co. on
April 3, the opening day of the major league baseball season.
   Not that the book is just about baseball. It's also about being
old and caring and sharing.
   Littlefield didn't know where his writing would lead when he
began his book. ``I got to several parts where I wanted to know
what hppened next myself,'' he said in an interview. ``I certainly
didn't know what was going to happen when I started it.''
   The story, interestingly, is told in two first-person accounts.
   One narrator, Pete Estey, is a retired baseball scout whose
playing career never got beyond the minor leagues. He lives in a
Flordia nursing home, listening to games on a radio and telling
baseball stories to Louise Brown, the other narrator. An avid
baseball fan from the Jackie Robinson days, she is religious,
strong and determined. She takes special care of patients at the
nursing home to keep them from slipping into the wards of oblivion.
   She also has a baseball-playing grandnephew, Jack, and she wants
to get him a shot at the big leagues.
   Littlefield didn't know Louise was going to be a character when
he started the book.
   ``I had a wonderful idea to have an old scout tell baseball
stories,'' he said. Estey was the sole narrator at first. ``Later
on Louise appeared ..., and I found I liked writing her very much.''
   Two old ballplayers, signed to their first contracts by Estey,
also figure in the book, and there is a woman in the nursing home
whose three dead daughters, Jackie Robinson and Babe Ruth visit her
from the clouds by sliding down the flagpole.
   The 40-year-old Littlefield is an associate professor of English
at Curry College in Milton, Mass. He also is sports commentator for
national public radio stations, including WBUR, a baseball throw
from the Boston Red Sox' Fenway Park.
   His commentaries sometimes take an off-beat approach. ``I think
that's the delight in being in sports; you can do a lot of things
you can't do (in other fields),'' he said.
   ``I take baseball very seriously. It fills a big aspect of my
life. I try not to be solemn about it. I try to recognize it as
fun.''
   His baseball career included Little League and summer camp teams
and intramural games at Yale University, where he also studied
under Robert Penn Warren. Now Littlefield plays on a fast-pitch
softball team in the Cambridge municipal league.
   It was through his radio work that he met Lennie Merullo, a
former player for the Chicago Cubs who lives in Reading and works
for the Major League Scouting Bureau in New England.
   Littlefield said he was impressed by Merullo's enthusiasm and
turned to him when he was developing the novel to bounce ideas off
him _ ``Could this happen? Would it be possible?'
   His knowledge insight into the way the elderly think came from
visiting his two grandmothers in nursing homes in New Jersey.
   ``I did have the idea of conveying to peole some of the pathos I
found in the two places,'' he said. ``As I went along, I found I
remembered far more than I thought.''
   He began writing ``Prospect'' in the summer of 1985 and
continued while on a sabbatical that fall. He finished last fall.
He did not work on it when Curry College was in session.
   ``What I discovered, I think, in the end was ... the discovery
that Pete makes that we are blessed with closeness when we don't
expect it,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv</NOTE>
