<FIRST>a e AM-APArts:Scandal Adv01   04-29 0642</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AP Arts: Scandal, Adv 01,0661</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv 01</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Mon AMs, May 1 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>A Sizzling ``Scandal'' Ignites London</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT WOLF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A decades-old sex caper is making headlines again
in Britain as the movie ``Scandal'' turns bygone political wounds
into the stuff of popular cinema.
   The film offers that peculiar blend of politics and sex which
has always caught on in Britain, where such scandals are regularly
recycled.
   ``Scandal'' tells of the liaison between former Cabinet Minister
John Profumo, secretary of war, with English showgirl Christine
Keeler, a relationship that exposed a Soviet connection and led to
a sensational trial and the suicide of osteopath Stephen Ward,
Keeler's social-climbing mentor.
   The ``Profumo Affair,'' as it came to be known, forced the war
minister to resign in 1963 when it was revealed that he was sharing
Keeler with a Soviet naval attache. The affair helped Profumo's
Conservative Party lose the general election a year later.
   John Hurt plays Ward and Joanne Whalley-Kilmer portrays Keeler.
Ian McKellen, who won a 1981 Tony for ``Amadeus,'' co-stars as
Profumo. American actress Bridget Fonda braves a London accent as
Keeler's sidekick, Mandy Rice-Davies.
   Critical response in England has ranged from praise for the
filmmakers' daring, to disapproval that a seamy story is being
dredged up again, especially after Profumo's prolonged penance as a
charity worker in the slums of London.
   Adam Mars-Jones in The Independent called the film ``a loving
and highly enjoyable portrait of the early 1960s'' with a
first-rate cast.
   But Peter McKay in The Evening Standard wrote: ``The whole,
boring morass is a quarter of a century old and it meant nothing at
the time, let alone now.''
   McKellen retorts: ``The themes brought out were in the end more
important than the comfort and privacy of one man's life.''
   The film is controversial in suggesting that Ward, far from
being an amoral cad, was duped into helping the secret service to
sexually compromise the Soviet attache.
   Borrowing from new reports, ``Scandal'' suggests that Ward was
abandoned by his spymasters and turned into a scapegoat to protect
the establishment from humiliation. This provoked an angry reply
from Anthony Hartley in the conservative Sunday Telegraph. He said
all the evidence showed that MI5, the domestic secret service,
believed Ward was indiscreet, unreliable and best avoided.
   ``Conspiracy theories are always a misleading approach to
history,'' wrote Hartley, ``and this one is no exception.''
   But producer Stephen Woolley says, ``We didn't make this up.
This happened. It has the same lack of logic that life has.''
   ``Scandal'' has done good box office in Britain, grossing over 3
million pounds ($5.1 million) since its March 3 release.
   In the United States, the film generated advance publicity when
a brief orgy scene earned it an X rating. The two-minute scene was
altered and the rating was changed to an R.
   Co-executive producer Harvey Weinstein, of Miramax Pictures in
New York, said ``Scandal'' was basically a fabulous love story.
   ``For men in my age group, Christine was like Bridget Bardot,
except she was involved in an international sex scandal,'' he said.
   Director Michael Caton-Jones said his movie was a call for
tolerance.
   ``Because Britain is so class-conscious, people always take much
more stock of what politicians say than anyone else,'' he said.
``Stephen and Christine were reprehensible types at the time,
(because) they were not ministers of state.''
   Caton-Jones, a Scot making his first feature movie, said
``Scandal'' made no claims towards documentary fact.
   ``There are so many different facets to it that you can't tell
the true story,'' he said. ``We wanted a focus that would allow us
to get as much in as possible, and it became obvious that the way
to do that was to concentrate on two characters, Stephen and
Christine, who directly affected it.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv</NOTE>
