<FIRST>a e BC-WeekendTV-RoeVsWade Adv12-14   04-29 0900</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Weekend TV-Roe Vs Wade, Adv 12-14,0919</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv12</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv13</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv14</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions of May 12-14 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Holly Hunter, `Roe vs. Wade' is More than a Movie</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ``Roe vs. Wade'' airs on NBC on May 15</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Holly Hunter, who was nominated for an Oscar
for the film ``Broadcast News,'' doesn't care much for television.
``I watch TV and I don't know what I'm seeing,'' she said. ``I'm
bored.''
   So why's she starring in ``Roe vs. Wade,'' NBC's dramatization
of the Supreme Court's decision to legalize abortion?
   It has more to do with an actor's convictions than with the
limits of an entertainment medium.
   ``I was interested in Roe vs. Wade. Well, I wasn't just
interested in it. I was active in it,'' Hunter said.
   An outspoken pro-choice advocate in real life, Hunter, 30,
played the pregnant plaintiff in ``Roe vs. Wade'' partly because
she feels a woman's right to a legal abortion is now in jeopardy.
The Supreme Court is weighing arguments in a Missouri case that
challenges Roe vs. Wade.
   ``I think what's going on says something about how women are
still riding shotgun,'' Hunter said. ``The fact that this case is
coming up again in the Supreme Court is kind of indicative of the
fact that the administration for the past eight years has really
taken a toll on civil rights in general, not excluding women's
rights.''
   In ``Roe vs. Wade,'' Hunter is Ellen Russell, a character based
on the real Roe plaintiff, Norma McCorvey. Russell is an unmarried,
unemployed Texas carnival barker. Her efforts to obtain an abortion
in a state where it was then illegal leads her to Sarah Weddington,
a lawyer eager to challenge the law.
   Weddington, played by Amy Madigan, argues the case all the way
to the Supreme Court, resulting in the landmark decision legalizing
abortion in 1973.
   Although ``Roe vs. Wade,'' shot under two phony names to avoid
protests, will almost certainly draw complaints from the
anti-abortion lobby, Hunter believes the movie is fair to both
sides of the debate. (Indeed, NBC insisted on more than 17 scripts
from ``Roe vs. Wade'' screenwriter Alison Cross to ensure the movie
didn't play favorites.)
   ``I think that the results of Jane Roe's efforts are heroic,''
Hunter said. ``It was a precedent that needed to be set real
desperately. Abortion needed to be made legal. But (Jane Roe) is
not a heroine at all. She's got glaring weaknesses and she's
extremely raw. ... And I thought that it was interesting to see
those two things.
   ``But I'm really happy Jane Roe didn't back out of it.''
   Both the pro-choice and anti-abortion forces in ``Roe vs.
Wade,'' Hunter said, ``are fully realized characters. And it didn't
have to be that way. But that absolutely gives it more credibility.
...
   ``I'm really glad it's not going to be a hammer-over-the-head
movie. I don't think there's any sentimentality in it. Most movies,
even features, if they're talking about issues, they make them so
black and white.''
   Hunter is confident that rather than being seen as a polemic,
``Roe vs. Wade'' will be viewed as educational and
thought-provoking.
   ``I think, actually, very few people know much of the story of
this case,'' Hunter said, including the fact that Jane Roe was
unable to have an abortion before the case was decided, and she
gave her baby up for adoption.
   ``(The movie) made my feeling about adoption more than
intellectual,'' Hunter said. ``Before, it was certainly something
that I believed in. But now that I've done Jane Roe, it just nailed
it in a little more securely: Adoption is just as personal a choice
as abortion.
   ``The response from so many people is that adoption is the
answer for any woman who wants to have an abortion. ... But the
fact is, adoption is a haphazardly, incompetently handled
institution. ...
   ``What if the mother is 23 years old, and she's been a hooker
for the past eight years, she has absolutely no money, she's got
six kids already and her husband _ or one of her tricks _ left her?
Who's going to want that baby? Who's going to adopt it? Like
nobody.''
   Even though ``Roe vs. Wade'' clearly represents a personal
project for Hunter, it does not mark any profound change in her
career. Her role in the upcoming film ``Miss Firecracker,'' now
playing in a few cities, is that of a wanna-be beauty queen, not a
partisan crusader.
   And the character she played so capably in ``Broadcast News'' _
a professionally gifted but emotionally crippled television news
producer _ was not out to change the world.
   ``Every movie I do I'm sure won't have political connotations,''
Hunter said. ``That's like me saying I'll never do a movie just for
the money. Are you kiddin', man?
   ``Yeah, I can do `Roe vs. Wade,' which I think is a fine
socially upstanding statement, and then maybe in five years, I'll
want to buy 300 acres of property somewhere. And say, `Well, this
project looks like it'd be fun, and they're offering me just a
(ton) of money. So I think I'll do it,''' Hunter said.
   ``Where I think the deceit lies is not in doing something for
money, but in doing it for money and not realizing that's why you
are.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for May 12-14</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890429-0139 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-29-89 0603EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f AM-BusinessMirror Adv02   04-29 0638</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Business Mirror, Adv 02,0657</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv02</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release AMs Tues., May 2</HEAD>
<HEAD>Do Short-Term Statistics Mean Anything?</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The eyes of many investment managers, inflation
worriers, and economic forecasters are watching still another
statistic, just as they've been doing every day for several weeks.
   They are scrutinizing digits, percentages and even decimal
points of the latest monthly business activity report from the
National Association of Purchasing Management, seeking in it signs
about the immediate future.
   Last week it was the report on consumer spending, after-tax
income and the savings rate. Later this week the microscope will be
turned on new-home sales, factory inventories, nonfarm payrolls,
consumer debt and similar reports.
   All this activity creates great excitement, ranging from terror
to elation. Pontificators orate. Portfolio managers change
investments. Learned academics comment sagely. The White House
often has something to say as well.
   But when all is said and done, the question remains: Do the
statistics of one month or one week mean very much, if anything?
Probably not, and the reasons are obvious and numerous.
   To begin with, there are seasonal and other aberrations that
cause short-term reports to deviate from the longer-term trend. As
more information comes in, revisions and adjustments often follow,
and corrections too.
   It is not at all uncommon, either, for one month's statistics to
signify something entirely different from the month before or the
one that follows. Moreover, opinions of the same statistics vary
from month to month.
   It is for reasons such as these that wise users of statistics
wait for confirmation, which doesn't occur until statistics for a
couple of months, at least, show the same configuration or until
related data offer support.
   Knowledge of this doesn't, of course, deter anyone. In an
economic world in which insight into the future can be turned into
megadollars, an entire industry exists on grabbing and analyzing
any numbers that float by.
   Among them are stock market analysts, academics with or seeking
a popular following, investors, the media, economists seeking to
prove that their theses are correct, and worry warts of various
stripes and spots.
   Worriers, and those who feed them, proliferate in an economy
that is seen these days as being on the edge of a precipice. Any
piece of statistical dust thus can be the weight that tips the
precarious balance.
   However, in a field of economics in which the most basic of
premises may be incorrect, how can a speck of dust be that
important? If doubts exist about the causes of inflation, for
example, can one month's statistics be that important?
   At the moment, one of the most widely held theories about the
current economy is that the budget deficits and federal debt are
likely to cause a catastrophe. It is probably the least
controversial of all current economic issues.
   However, some of the sharpest brains in American economics
disagree.
   Prof. Robert Heilbroner and Peter Bernstein, authors of ``The
Debt and the Deficit,'' state the national debt will not, as is
widely thought, impoverish our grandchildren, that only a small
percentage of it is owed to foreigners, and that the national debt
and deficit are not large by historic standards.
   They are not alone. Prof. Robert Eisner of Harvard, former
president of the American Economic Association, contends that the
true deficit is much smaller than thought, and that everyone would
know it with proper accounting methods.
   If such an enormous disagreement exists about such a fundamental
concept of American life, why should one vagrant grain of
statistical dust have an important and even enormous impact on the
present and future?
   It is something to think about this week when you read the
reports about construction spending and installment credit and
factory inventories and nonfarm payrolls.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv AMs Tues., May 2</NOTE>
</DOC>
